# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aftermath-of-world-war-ii
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The **1939–1940 Winter Offensive** (Chinese: 冬季攻勢) was a major engagement between the National Revolutionary Army and Imperial Japanese Army during the Second Sino-Japanese War.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] It constitutes the first major counter-offensive on multiple fronts of Chinese forces in the war.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Although it failed to achieve its original objectives, later studies have shown that it came as a blow to the Japanese forces.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The Japanese military command had not expected the Chinese to be able to launch an offensive operation at such a large scale.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] By April 1940, the Japanese army had successfully fought the operation to a halt.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] However, a Japanese counter-offensive to seize Ningxia failed and was defeated in Suiyuan by Chinese Muslim forces.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The Chinese had repulsed two Japanese offensives in the summer at the Battle of Suixian-Zaoyang and in fall at the 1st Battle of Changsha.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] They believed that the Japanese forces were now too dissipated to take and hold new territory and would not be able to launch large offensives unless they received more reinforcements.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] However, by defending interior lines and with control of the lines of communication, they could still shift forces and launch local offensives to damage Chinese forces or mop up guerrillas in the rear areas.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Additionally, during 1939, the Japanese were replacing many of their large four-regiment square Divisions with the smaller three regiment triangular Divisions and weak Independent Mixed Brigades.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] This weakening of forces encouraged the Chinese to plan a large offensive to exploit that fact.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The Chinese objective in the offensive was to take the initiative by conducting multiple-front attacks to tie down Japanese forces.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] They intended to use their position of exterior lines to advantage to prevent the Japanese from launching new local offensives or shifting their forces to concentrate for a large offensive.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The main effort was to be by the 2nd, 3rd, 5th and 9th War Areas, located on the more northeastern side of China, closest to Japan, which received all newly trained and reorganized units.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Secondary efforts in support of the main efforts or as diversions were to be conducted by 1st, 4th, 8th, Shandong-Jiangsu and Hebei-Chahar War Areas, further south or west from Japan, with their existing units.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Despite this, the 40th Corps and 27th Corps accomplished their aim of pinning down the Japanese in the Zhangzi and Changzhi area.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] However, in southwestern Shanxi, the main effort of 2nd War Area and of the whole North China offensive failed to seize the major towns on the railroad or Japanese strongpoints that were their objectives or to cut the Tongpu railway, except for the area between Wenxi and Anyi.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] At the end of the campaign, the 2nd War Area claimed that 13,770 Japanese killed or wounded.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The 1st War Area reported that 5,130 Japanese killed, and seems to have accomplished its mission of tying down Japanese troops in its area of operations.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The 8th War Area, after a see-saw campaign, had succeeded in rolling the Japanese back to Baotou in the Battle of Wuyuan.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Guerrilla forces in the Hebei-Chahar and Shandong-Jiangsu War Area carried out attacks but apparently without decisive results, and in the Shandong peninsula they received a serious counterattack.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] In 1937, the Chinese government picked up intelligence that the Japanese planned to install a puppet Hui Muslim regime around Suiyuan and Ningxia, and had sent agents to the region.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The *Middlesboro Daily News* ran an article by Owen Lattimore which reported on Japan's planned offensive into the Muslim region in 1938, which predicted that the Japanese would suffer a crushing defeat at the hands of the Muslims.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The Japanese planned to invade Ningxia from Suiyuan in 1939 and create a Hui Muslim puppet state.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The next year, however, the Japanese were defeated by the Kuomintang Muslim Gen.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Ma Hongbin, causing the plan to collapse.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] His Hui Muslim troops launched further attacks against Japan in the Battle of West Suiyuan.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] In Suiyuan, 300 Mongol collaborators serving the Japanese were fought off by a single Muslim who held the rank of major at the Battle of Wulan Obo in April.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Muslim Generals Ma Hongkui and Ma Hongbin defended west Suiyuan, especially in Wuyuan, in 1940.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Ma Hongbin commanded the 81st Corps, which suffered heavy casualties, but they eventually repulsed the Japanese and defeated them.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Japan made heavy use of chemical weapons against China to make up for lack of numbers in combat and because China did not have any poison gas stockpiles of its own to retaliate.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Japan also used poison gas against Chinese Muslim armies at the Battle of Wuyuan and the Battle of West Suiyuan.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] River North Army accomplished little and was driven back behind the river by December 23, freeing up units of the Japanese 13th Division for use elsewhere.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The Japanese held Right Flank Army in the Zhongxiang area far from the planned stop line from Xinshi to Songhe and Pingba.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The Japanese contained Left Flank Army or (River East Army) far from its final objectives.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Southern Honan Army did attack the enemy 3rd Division in the area north of Yingshan and Xishuanghe and send a strong force to cut enemy lines of communications in the area of Guangshui and Xinyang.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Its main force was to attack in the area of Xinyang and occupy it.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Neither of these objectives was achieved despite the commitment of the 31st Army Group.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Eastern Hupei Guerrilla force did not advance to the enemy rear areas at Guangshui, Huayuan and Hankow to check enemy movement along the railroad.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] They never got near those objectives, leaving the Japanese free to move troops along the rails to meet other attacks.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] One of the main objectives that the Chinese managed to retake was the city of Kaifeng.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] After two weeks of fighting, they managed to liberate the city on December 16th, capturing a good amount of Japanese equipment.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Soon after, however, they were pushed out of the city again.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] According to the history of the 65th Infantry Regiment of the Japanese 13th Division, the number of combat deaths for the regiment in the Winter Offensive was as high as 303.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] After routing the Japanese force coming from Longxian on January 1, the 54th Corps recaptured that town on the 2nd.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Guandu fell on the 4th and Qingtang on January 5.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The Japanese retreated to Shatian while 54th Corps advanced southwest to Shijiao.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] On January 3 the 2nd Provisional Corps laid siege to Yingde and took it on the 5th.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] It then continued to advance to Lianjiangkou while Japanese remnants fled southwest and took Qingcheng on the north bank of the Lian River, linking up with Japanese forces across the river to the south.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Subsequently, portions of 64th Corps and 2nd Provisional Corps recovered Qingcheng on January 10.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Across the river the next day 14th Division of 54th Corps recovered Pajiangkou and to the east Conghua fell to the detachment of 35th Army Group.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] Yuantan along the Guangzhou–Hankou railway fell the following day.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The main force of 35th Army Group moved along the west bank of the Bei River near Zhaoqing, and 54th Corps and a portion of 12th Army Group moved to take up positions at Hengshi, Liangkou, Lutian and Meikang.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The 4th War Area reported more than 10,300 enemy killed, 100 rifles and large amount of supplies captured.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The Chinese Army suffered 6,564 killed, 4,595 wounded, and 2,828 missing in the First Battle of Northern Guangdong from December 17, 1939, to January 10, 1940, and claimed to have captured 1 Japanese officer and 1 Japanese soldier.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The Japanese 21st Army suffered 293 killed and 1,281 wounded in the Wengyuan-Yingde operation from the middle to the end of December 1939 and claimed to have killed 16,312 and captured 1,196 Chinese troops.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] According to each participating Japanese units' battle report, the 18th Division (excluding the 56th Infantry Regiment) suffered 62 killed, 162 wounded, and 1 missing in the Wengyuan-Yingde operation from December 14, 1939, to January 10, 1940.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The 56th Infantry Regiment of the 18th Division suffered 3 killed and 1 wounded in the operation from December 23 to December 31, 1939.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The 104th Division suffered 302 killed and 735 wounded in the operation from November 20, 1939, to January 13, 1940.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] The Guards Mixed Brigade suffered 106 killed, 221 wounded, and 20 missing in the operation from December 16, 1939, to January 4, 1940.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1939-1940-winter-offensive] However, with the restricted frontage, and reinforcements sent from Central China the Japanese were able to shift forces to relieve their forces in South Guangxi.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The **1944 Bulgarian coup d'état**, also known as the **9 September coup d'état** (Bulgarian: Деветосептемврийски преврат, romanized: *Devetoseptemvriyski prevrat*), was a coup that overthrew the government of Kingdom of Bulgaria on the eve of 9 September 1944.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] During the Communist era, official propaganda called the coup the **People's Uprising of 9 September** on the grounds of the broad unrest and the **Socialist Revolution** as it was a turning point politically and the beginning of radical reforms towards Soviet-style socialism.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The USSR had declared war on the Kingdom of Bulgaria 4 days earlier and units of its Third Russian Front of the Red Army had entered Bulgaria 3 days after.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] Demonstrations, strikes, revolts broke out in many cities and villages (6 - 7 September) and local government power had been taken by Bulgarian Fatherland Front (FF) forces (without Red Army help) in Varna, Burgas, and other locations.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] As a direct result, the government of Prime Minister Konstantin Muraviev was overthrown and replaced with a government of the FF led by Kimon Georgiev.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] Bulgaria immediately joined the Allies and fought against Nazi Germany.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The Kingdom of Bulgaria became a republic after the Bulgarian republic referendum in 1946.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] Large-scale political, economic and social changes were introduced to the country.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The coup resulted in Bulgaria entering into the Soviet sphere of influence and the beginning of the Bulgarian People's Republic.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] On 26 August 1944, the government of Ivan Bagryanov had verbally declared Bulgaria's neutrality in the war under the threat of the Red Army's offensive in neighbouring Romania.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] At the same time, in Egypt the government had entered separate peace talks with the United Kingdom and the United States, hoping to secure the dispatch of British and American troops in Bulgaria.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] On the same day, the Central Committee of the Bulgarian Workers' Party (BWP) proclaimed the assumption of power by means of a popular uprising to be its official task.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] A government of the Bulgarian Agrarian National Union (BANU) "Vrabcha 1", until then in opposition, was formed on 2 September 1944, headed by Konstantin Muraviev.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] It continued the peace talks, declared its support for democratic reforms and ordered the withdrawal of German Army troops from Bulgaria.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] At the same time, the guerrilla actions of the partisans did not cease, the alliance with Nazi Germany was not disbanded and no attempts were made to normalize the relations with Moscow, causing the Soviet Union to treat the new government with suspicion.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] On 5 September 1944, the Soviet Union declared war on Bulgaria.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The Central Committee of the BWP and the general staff of the People's Liberation Revolt Army commenced, on 5 September, planning of a coup d'état.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The plan was further detailed on 8 September.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] According to the plan, the coordinated actions of the partisans, the BWP combat groups and the pro-Fatherland Front army detachments would assume power and effective control of government during the night of 9 September.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The stated goal of the coup d'état was the "overthrowing of the fascist authorities and the establishment of popular-democratic power of the Fatherland Front".
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] Unrest began all around Bulgaria on 6 September and 7 September, with the strikes of the Pernik miners and the Sofia tram employees, as well as the general strikes in Plovdiv and Gabrovo.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The prisons in Pleven, Varna and Sliven had their political prisoners released; 170 localities were entered by partisan detachments between 6 September and 8 September.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] In many cities and villages, the strikes and meetings grew into armed clashes with the police, with victims on both sides.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] On 8 September, the Red Army entered Bulgaria meeting with no opposition on the order of the new Bulgarian government.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] On the eve of 9 September, army units together with Fatherland Front detachments captured key locations in Sofia, such as the Ministry of War, the Ministry of Internal Affairs, the post, the telegraph, the radio, and the railway station.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] On 9 September, on the order of the NOVA commander-in-chief Dobri Terpeshev, all partisan units descended from the mountains and took over villages and cities' governments.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] In most places, this was not met with much resistance, but in other cases army and police units loyal to the old government put up violent resistance to the Fatherland Front forces.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] In Sofia, Plovdiv, the region of Pernik, Shumen and Haskovo the old regime's supporters were defeated by military action with the army coming under the effective control of the Fatherland Front.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The establishment of the new leadership happened at the latest in Haskovo, where partisans and other antifascists seized the artillery barracks on 12 September, but suffered many casualties, as the negotiations with the commanding officers failed to reach a compromise.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] As of 9 September, the Red Army had not reached Sofia but remained in northeastern Bulgaria, as the Bulgarian communists were capable of assuming power without any aid.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The Fatherland Front government included representatives of the BWP, BANU "Pladne", the Bulgarian Social Democratic Workers' Party (Broad Socialists) and Zveno.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The former Prime Minister Konstantin Muraviev was arrested, as were Tsar Simeon II's regents, members of the former government, and some army detachment heads.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] On 10 September, the police was abolished and replaced with a popular militia consisting mainly of recent partisans; 8,130 political prisoners were released from the prisons, and the concentration camps of the former regime (e.g.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] Gonda voda, Krasto pole, Lebane) were closed down.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The fascist organizations were banned, as were their publications.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The former regents, Prince Kiril, Bogdan Filov, and Nikola Mihov, were executed on 1 February 1945.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] On 8 September 1946, a referendum about the further destiny of the monarchy was held.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] Based on the results of the referendum, Bulgaria was declared People's Republic on 15 September 1946.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] After 9 September 1944, the Bulgarian Army joined the Third Ukrainian Front and contributed to the defeat of Nazism in Europe, helping drive out the Germans from much of Yugoslavia and Hungary, reaching as far as Klagenfurt in Austria by April 1945.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] Although Bulgaria was not recognized as a true member of the Allies, it still managed to retain Southern Dobruja which it had acquired in 1940 per the Treaty of Craiova.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] In December 1944, the People's Court was formed by the government of Kimon Georgiev.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] Its stated goal was to condemn the persons guilty for Bulgaria's participation in World War II.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] Between 4,000 and 30,000 people were killed or missing in just the first four months after the communist regime overtook Bulgaria.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] Later, the Bulgarian Communist Party consolidated its leading role in the ruling Fatherland Front coalition, reducing its members from 5 to 2 political parties (the other being the Agrarian Union), leading to the BCP's sole domination over Bulgarian politics up until 1989.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-bulgarian-coup-d-état] The Tarnovo Constitution was overthrown and replaced in 1947 by the new pro-communist republican Dimitrov Constitution after the successful republic referendum in 1946.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The **1944 Romanian coup d'état**, better known in Romanian historiography as the **Act of 23 August** (Romanian: *Actul de la 23 august*), was a coup d'état led by King Michael I of Romania during World War II on 23 August 1944.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] With the support of several political parties, the king removed the government of Ion Antonescu, which had aligned Romania with Nazi Germany, after the Axis front in northeastern Romania collapsed in the face of a successful Soviet offensive.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The Romanian Army declared a unilateral ceasefire with the Soviet Red Army on the Moldavian front, an event viewed as decisive in the Allied advances against the Axis powers in the European theatre of World War II.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The coup was supported by the Romanian Communist Party, the Social Democratic Party, the National Liberal Party, and the National Peasants' Party who had coalesced into the National Democratic Bloc in June 1944.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] According to Silviu Brucan, the two main conspirators from the Communist Party's side were Emil Bodnăraș and Lucrețiu Pătrășcanu, who contacted King Michael to prepare a *coup d'état* against Ion Antonescu.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The first meeting between King Michael's representatives with the Communists was during the night of 13–14 June 1944 in a secret house of the communists, at 103 Calea Moșilor.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Apart from the two communist conspirators, participants in the meeting were Gen.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Dumitru Dămăceanu, while King Michael was represented by Baron Ioan Mocsony-Stârcea (marshal of the palace), Mircea Ionnițiu (private secretary) and Grigore Niculescu-Buzești (diplomatic adviser).
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The King's representatives presented the Gigurtu plan, through which the King would meet Baron Manfred Freiherr von Killinger, the German ambassador in Bucharest, to discuss the replacement of Antonescu with a cabinet led by Ion Gigurtu.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The Communist Party thought that this plan was "naïve and dangerous", as it would have alerted the Gestapo and that it would have meant even more German espionage.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] After this, a coalition government of the National Democratic Bloc (the National Peasants' Party, the National Liberal Party, the Social Democratic Party and the Romanian Communist Party) would take power.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] This proposal was accepted by both the military representatives and the King's advisers, who then convinced King Michael that it was the best solution.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] On 23 August 1944, the king joined with pro-Allied opposition politicians and led a successful coup with support from the army.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The king, who was initially considered to be not much more than a "figurehead", was able to successfully depose Antonescu.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The king offered a non-confrontational retreat to Killinger, but the Germans considered the coup "reversible" and tried to turn the situation around by military attacks.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] On 23 August 1944, the King met with Prime Minister Ion Antonescu, Foreign Affairs Minister Mihai Antonescu (no relation) and General Constantin Sănătescu.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] During discussions that lasted an hour, Ion Antonescu informed the King of the situation at the frontlines.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] King Michael asked Antonescu to get out of the war and sign an armistice with the Allies and the Soviets.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Antonescu retorted that the armistice would be nullified by Germany and refused to commit to an armistice, especially with the Soviet Union.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] A colonel and four soldiers came in and arrested the Prime Minister.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Later that night, at 10 pm, the King announced over the radio that Antonescu had been deposed and an armistice with the Allied Powers and the Soviet Union would be accepted.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The Romanian forces — namely the First Army, the Second Army (under formation), the remnants of the Third Army and the Fourth Army (one corps) — were under orders from the king to defend Romania against any German attacks.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The king then offered to put Romania's battered armies on the side of the Allies.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Hungarian-American historian John Lukacs praised the coup, writing: "In August 1944, the Rumanians executed the most successful *coup d'etat* during World War II.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Due to Romania's successful defection, most of the country's economy had survived virtually intact.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The ensuing reconstruction of the oil industry showed that Romania had less power of refusal under Stalin than under Hitler.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Unlike Italy's earlier capitulation, Romania's initiative began to unravel the Axis.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Within one month, Bulgaria and Finland also changed sides, the Slovak National Uprising began, and a failed coup was attempted in Croatia on 18 September.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Economically, Albert Speer regarded Romania's defection as decisive, because it not only deprived the Axis of Romanian oil but also definitively cut off access to vital supplies of Turkish chromium.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The loss of Romania's oil resulted in Hitler's first admission that the war was lost.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] All of these were accomplished with minimal damage to Romanian infrastructure, as the country's core never became a battlefield.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The coup also marked the last instance when Romania's actions significantly influenced the wider course of the war.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The coup sped the Red Army's advance into Romania.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Formal Allied recognition of the *de facto* change of orientation of Romania in the war came on 12 September 1944.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Until this date, Soviet troops started moving into Romania, taking approximately 140,000 Romanian prisoners of war.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] About 130,000 Romanian POWs were transported to the Soviet Union, where many perished in prison camps.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The armistice was signed on the same date, 12 September 1944, on Allied terms.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] In line with Article 14 of the Armistice Agreement, two Romanian People's Tribunals were set up to try suspected war criminals.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Article 19 stipulated the return to Romania of "Transylvania or the greater part of it".
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] This phrasing conveyed the possibility of a revision of the Treaty of Trianon border, and it was meant to tempt Hungary to also cease fighting alongside Germany.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] At the same time the article also declared Vienna Award "null and void".
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] On 15 October 1944, regent of Hungary Miklós Horthy indeed tried to follow Romania's example and negotiate a surrender, but his attempt was thwarted.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Northern Transylvania was under Soviet military administration from November 1944 to March 1945.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] On 9 March 1945, three days after the formation of the Petru Groza cabinet, Stalin approved the return of all of Northern Transylvania to Romanian administration.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Subsequent Hungarian efforts to recover part of Northern Transylvania were in vain.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] In October 1944, Winston Churchill, Prime Minister of the United Kingdom, as part of a proposed agreement with Soviet leader Joseph Stalin on how to divide Eastern Europe into spheres of influence after the war.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] It was reportedly agreed that Soviet Union would have a "90% share of influence" in Romania.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The Romanian Army, from the armistice until the end of the war, were fighting alongside the Soviets against Germany and its remaining allies.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] They fought in Transylvania, Hungary and Czechoslovakia.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] In May 1945 the Romanian First and Fourth Armies took part in the Prague Offensive.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] The Romanians suffered a total of 169,822 casualties (in all causes) fighting on the Allied side.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Ion Antonescu was placed under arrest; the new prime minister, Lt.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Constantin Sănătescu, gave custody of Antonescu to Romanian communists who would turn the former dictator over to the Soviets on 1 September.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] He was later returned to Romania, where he was tried and executed in 1946.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] For his actions, King Michael was awarded the Soviet Order of Victory by Joseph Stalin in 1945.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] He was also awarded the highest degree (Chief Commander) of the Legion of Merit by President Harry S.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Nevertheless, he functioned as little more than a figurehead under the new régime.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] He was finally forced to abdicate and leave the country in 1947.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] This allowed the Communists to set up a communist government.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1944-romanian-coup-d-état] Michael remained in exile until after the 1989 Romanian revolution and was only allowed to return to the country in 1992.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] A general election was held in the United Kingdom on Thursday 5 July 1945.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] With the ongoing Second World War still fresh in the minds of voters, the opposition Labour Party led by Clement Attlee won a landslide victory with a majority of 146 seats, defeating the incumbent Conservative-led government under Prime Minister Winston Churchill.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The result reflected widespread public concern about the future direction of the United Kingdom in the post-war period.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The election's campaigning was focused on leadership of the country and its postwar future.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Opinion polls when the election was called showed strong approval ratings for Churchill, but Labour had held a lead in voting intention polls since 1943.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour won a landslide victory, gaining 239 seats for a total majority of 146 with 49.7% of the popular vote, allowing Attlee to become prime minister.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The party also won two seats in a walkover, the last time any seat in the House of Commons went uncontested in a general election.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] This was Labour's first outright majority and enabled Attlee to begin implementing the party's post-war reforms.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The result was a major shock for the Conservatives, who lost 189 seats despite winning 36.2% of the vote, having campaigned on the assumption that Churchill's wartime leadership would secure victory.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberal Party suffered a net loss of nine seats and its leader Archibald Sinclair lost his seat, while the Liberal National Party lost 22 seats, including that of its leader Ernest Brown.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] A total of 324 new MPs entered the House of Commons, a record that stood until 2024.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Additionally, the beginning of the Attlee ministry paralleled the beginning of the Truman administration in the United States.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The 11.7% swing from the Conservatives to an opposition party is the largest since the Acts of Union 1800; the Conservative loss of the vote exceeded that of the 1906 Liberal landslide ousting of a Conservative administration.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] It was also the first election since 1906 in which the Conservatives did not win a plurality (relative majority) of the popular vote.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Churchill remained actively involved in politics and returned as prime minister after leading his party into the 1951 general election.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] For the Liberal National Party the election was their last as a distinct party, as they merged with the Conservatives in 1947 (although they operated as a subsidiary party of the Conservatives until 1968) while Ernest Brown resigned from politics in the aftermath of the election.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Held less than two months following VE Day, this was the first general election since 1935, as general elections had been suspended by Parliament during the Second World War.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Clement Attlee, the leader of the Labour Party, refused Winston Churchill's offer of continuing the wartime coalition until the Allied defeat of Japan.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] On 15 June, King George VI dissolved Parliament, which had been sitting for nearly ten years without an election.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The Labour manifesto, *Let Us Face the Future*, included promises of nationalisation, economic planning, full employment, a National Health Service, and a system of social security.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The manifesto proved popular with the electorate, selling one and a half million copies.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Churchill's Declaration to the Voters*, on the other hand, included progressive ideas on key social issues but was relatively vague on the idea of postwar economic control, and the party was associated with high levels of unemployment in the 1930s.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] It failed to convince voters that it could effectively deal with unemployment in a postwar Britain.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] In May 1945, when the war in Europe ended, Churchill's approval ratings stood at 83%, but the Labour Party had held an 18% poll lead as of February 1945.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The polls for some seats were delayed until 12 July and in Nelson and Colne until 19 July because of local wakes weeks.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The results were counted and declared on 26 July to allow time to transport the votes of those serving overseas.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Victory over Japan Day ensued on 15 August.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The caretaker government, led by Churchill, was heavily defeated.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The Labour Party led by Attlee won a landslide victory and gained a majority of 146 seats.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] It was the first election in which Labour gained a majority of seats and the first in which it won a relative majority (plurality) of votes.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The election was a disaster for the Liberal Party, which lost all of its urban seats, and marked its transition from being a party of government to a party of the political fringe.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Its leader, Archibald Sinclair, lost his rural seat of Caithness and Sutherland.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] That was the last general election until 2019 in which a major party leader lost their seat, but Sinclair lost only by six votes in a very tight three-way contest.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The Liberal National Party fared even worse by losing two-thirds of its seats and falling behind the Liberals in seat count for the first time since the parties split in 1931.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] It was the final election that the Liberal Nationals fought as an autonomous party, as they merged with the Conservative Party two years later although they continued to exist as a subsidiary party of the Conservatives until 1968.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Future prominent figures who entered Parliament included Harold Wilson, James Callaghan, Barbara Castle, Michael Foot and Hugh Gaitskell.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Future Conservative Prime Minister Harold Macmillan lost his seat, but he returned to Parliament at a by-election later that year.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The greatest factor in Labour's dramatic win appeared to be its policy of social reform.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] In one opinion poll, 41% of respondents considered housing to be the most important issue that faced the country, 15% stated the Labour policy of full employment, 7% mentioned social security, 6% nationalisation, and just 5% international security, which was emphasised by the Conservatives.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The Beveridge Report, published in 1942, proposed the creation of a welfare state.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] It called for a dramatic turn in British social policy, with provision for nationalised healthcare, expansion of state-funded education, National Insurance and a new housing policy.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The report was extremely popular, and copies of its findings were widely purchased, turning it into a best-seller.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The Labour Party adopted the report eagerly, and the Conservatives (including Churchill, who did not regard the reforms as socialist) accepted many of the principles of the report, but claimed that they were not affordable.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour offered a new comprehensive welfare policy, reflecting a consensus that social changes were needed.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The Conservatives were not willing to make the same changes that Labour proposed, and appeared out of step with public opinion.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour played to the concept of "winning the peace" that would follow the war.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Possibly for that reason, there was especially strong support for Labour in the armed services, which feared the unemployment and homelessness to which the soldiers of the First World War had returned.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] It has been claimed that the left-wing bias of teachers in the armed services was a contributing factor, but that argument has generally not carried much weight, and the failure of the Conservative governments in the 1920s to deliver a "land fit for heroes" was likely more important.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour had also been given during the war the opportunity to display to the electorate its domestic competence in government, under men such as Attlee as Deputy Prime Minister, Herbert Morrison at the Home Office and Ernest Bevin at the Ministry of Labour.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The differing wartime strategies of the two parties likewise gave Labour an advantage.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour continued to attack prewar Conservative governments for their inactivity in tackling Hitler, reviving the economy and rearming Britain, but Churchill was less interested in furthering his party, much to the chagrin of many of its members and MPs.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Though voters respected and liked Churchill's wartime record, they were more distrustful of the Conservative Party's domestic and foreign policy record in the late 1930s.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Churchill and the Conservatives are also generally considered to have run a poor campaign in comparison to Labour.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Churchill's personal popularity remained high; hence, the Conservatives were confident of victory and based much of their election campaign on that, rather than proposing new programmes.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] However, people distinguished between Churchill and his party, a contrast that Labour repeatedly emphasised throughout the campaign.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Voters also harboured doubts over Churchill's ability to lead the country on the domestic front.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] The writer and soldier Anthony Burgess remarked that Churchill, who then often wore a colonel's uniform, was not nearly as popular with soldiers at the front as with officers and civilians.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Burgess noted that Churchill often smoked cigars in front of soldiers who had not had a decent cigarette in days.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] In addition to the poor Conservative general election strategy, Churchill went so far as to accuse Attlee of seeking to behave as a dictator, despite Attlee's service as part of Churchill's war cabinet.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] In the most famous incident of the campaign, Churchill's first election broadcast on 4 June backfired dramatically and memorably.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Denouncing his former coalition partners, he declared that Labour "would have to fall back on some form of a Gestapo" to impose socialism on Britain.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Attlee responded the next night by ironically thanking the prime minister for demonstrating to the people the difference between "Churchill the great wartime leader" and "Churchill the peacetime politician" and argued the case for public control of industry.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Another blow to the Conservative campaign was the memory of the 1930s policy of appeasement, conducted by Churchill's Conservative predecessors, Neville Chamberlain and Stanley Baldwin, that had been widely discredited for allowing Adolf Hitler's Germany to become too powerful.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Labour had strongly advocated appeasement until 1938, but the interwar period had been dominated by Conservatives.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] With the exception of two brief minority Labour governments in 1924 and 1929–1931, the Conservatives had been in power for all of the interwar period.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] As a result, the Conservatives were generally blamed for the era's mistakes: appeasement, inflation and the unemployment of the Great Depression.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Many voters felt that although the First World War had been won, the peace that followed had been lost.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] All comparisons are with the winning party in the 1935 election; the aim is to provide a comparison with the previous general election.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] This list includes seats where the incumbent was standing down and therefore there was no possibility of a particular person being defeated.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1945-united-kingdom-general-election] Polls showed a lead for Labour since 1943, except for one poll in June 1945 when both Labour and the Conservatives tied on 45%.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] An institutional referendum (Italian: *referendum istituzionale*, or *referendum sulla forma istituzionale dello Stato*) was held by universal suffrage in the Kingdom of Italy on 2 June 1946, a key event of contemporary Italian history.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Until 1946, Italy was a kingdom ruled by the House of Savoy, reigning since the unification of Italy in 1861 and previously rulers of the Kingdom of Sardinia.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In 1922, the rise of Benito Mussolini and the creation of the Fascist regime in Italy, which eventually resulted in engaging the country in World War II alongside Nazi Germany, considerably weakened the role of the royal house.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Following the Italian Civil War and the Liberation of Italy from Axis troops in 1945, a popular referendum on the institutional form of the state was called the next year and resulted in voters choosing the replacement of the monarchy with a republic.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The 1946 Italian general election to elect the Constituent Assembly of Italy was held on the same day.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] As with the simultaneous Constituent Assembly elections, the referendum was not held in the Julian March, in the province of Zara or the province of Bolzano, which were still under occupation by Allied forces pending a final settlement of the status of the territories.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The results were proclaimed by the Supreme Court of Cassation on 10 June 1946: 12,717,923 citizens in favor of the republic and 10,719,284 citizens in favor of the monarchy.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The event is commemorated annually by the *Festa della Repubblica*.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] With the entry into force of the new Constitution of the Italian Republic, on 1 January 1948, Enrico De Nicola became the first to assume the functions of president of Italy.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] It marked the first time that most of the Italian Peninsula was under a single republican government since the fall of the Roman Republic.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In the history of Italy there are several so-called "republican" governments that have followed one another over time.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Examples are the ancient Roman Republic and the medieval maritime republics.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] From Cicero to Niccolò Machiavelli, Italian philosophers have imagined the foundations of political science and republicanism.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] But it was Giuseppe Mazzini who revived the republican idea in Italy in the 19th century.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] An Italian nationalist in the historical radical tradition and a proponent of a republicanism of social-democratic inspiration, Mazzini helped define the modern European movement for popular democracy in a republican state.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Mazzini formulated a concept known as "thought and action" in which thought and action must be joined and every thought must be followed by action, therefore rejecting intellectualism and the notion of divorcing theory from practice.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The foundation of the Young Italy constitutes a key moment of the Italian Risorgimento and this republican program precedes in time the proposals for the unification of Italy of Vincenzo Gioberti and Cesare Balbo, aimed at reunifying the Italian territory under the presidency of the Pope.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Subsequently, the philosopher Carlo Cattaneo promoted a secular and republican Italy in the extension of Mazzini's ideas, but organized as a federal republic.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The political projects of Mazzini and Cattaneo were thwarted by the action of the Piedmontese Prime Minister Camillo Benso, Count of Cavour, and Giuseppe Garibaldi.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The latter set aside his republican ideas to favor Italian unity.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] After having obtained the conquest of the whole of southern Italy during the Expedition of the Thousand, Garibaldi handed over the conquered territories to the king of Sardinia Victor Emmanuel II, which were annexed to the Kingdom of Sardinia after a plebiscite.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] This earned him heavy criticism from numerous republicans who accused him of treason.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] While a laborious administrative unification began, a first Italian parliament was elected and, on 17 March 1861, Victor Emmanuel II was proclaimed king of Italy.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] From 1861 to 1946, Italy was a constitutional monarchy founded on the Albertine Statute, named after the king who promulgated it in 1848, Charles Albert of Sardinia.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The parliament included a Senate, whose members were appointed by the king, and a Chamber of Deputies, elected by census vote.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In 1861 only 2% of Italians had the right to vote.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In the political panorama of the time there was a republican political movement which had its martyrs, such as the soldier Pietro Barsanti.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Barsanti was a supporter of republican ideas, and was a soldier in the Royal Italian Army with the rank of corporal.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] He was sentenced to death and shot in 1870 for having favored an insurrectional attempt against the Savoy monarchy and is therefore considered the first martyr of the modern Italian Republic and a symbol of republican ideals in Italy.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The balance of power between the Chamber and Senate initially shifted in favor of the Senate, composed mainly of nobles and industrial figures.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Little by little, the Chamber of Deputies took on more and more importance with the evolution of the bourgeoisie and the large landowners, concerned with economic progress, but supporters of order and a certain social conservatism.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The Republicans took part in the elections to the Italian Parliament, and in 1853 they formed the Action Party around Giuseppe Mazzini.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Although in exile, Mazzini was elected in 1866, but refused to take his seat in parliament.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Carlo Cattaneo was elected deputy in 1860 and 1867, but refused so as not to have to swear loyalty to the House of Savoy.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The problem of the oath of loyalty to the monarchy, necessary to be elected, was the subject of controversy within the republican forces.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In 1873 Felice Cavallotti, one of the most committed Italian politicians against the monarchy, preceded his oath with a declaration in which he reaffirmed his republican beliefs.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In 1882, a new electoral law lowered the census limit for voting rights, increasing the number of voters to over two million, equal to 7% of the population.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In the same year the Italian Workers' Party was created, which in 1895 became the Italian Socialist Party.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In 1895 the intransigent republicans agreed to participate in the political life of the Kingdom, establishing the Italian Republican Party.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Two years later, the far left reached its historical maximum level in Parliament with 81 deputies, for the three radical-democratic, socialist components and Republican.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] With the death of Felice Cavallotti in 1898, the radical left gave up on posing the institutional problem.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In Italian politics, the socialist party progressively divided into two tendencies: a maximalist one, led among others by Arturo Labriola and Enrico Ferri, and supporting the use of strikes; the other, reformist and pro-government, was led by Filippo Turati.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] A nationalist movement emerged, led in particular by Enrico Corradini, as well as a Catholic social and democratic movement, the National Democratic League, led by Romolo Murri.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In 1904, Pope Pius X authorized Catholics to participate individually in political life, but in 1909 he condemned the National Democratic League created by Romolo Murri, who was excommunicated.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Finally, a law of 3 June 1912 marked Italy's evolution towards a certain political liberalism by establishing universal male suffrage.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In 1914, at the outbreak of World War I, Italy began to be counted among the world's liberal democracies.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] After World War I, Italian political life was animated by four great movements.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Two of these movements were in favor of democratic development within the framework of existing monarchical institutions: the reformist socialists and the Italian People's Party.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Two other movements challenged these institutions: the Republican Party on the one hand, and the maximalist socialists.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In the 1919 elections, the parties most imbued with republican ideology (the maximalist socialists and the Republican Party) won, obtaining 165 out of 508 seats in the Chamber of Deputies.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In the 1921 elections, after the foundation of the Italian Communist Party, the three parties republican, maximalist socialist and communist obtained 145 deputies out of 535.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Overall, at the beginning of the interwar period, less than 30% of those elected were in favor of the establishment of a republican regime.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In this context, the rise of Benito Mussolini's fascist movement was based on the bitterness generated by the "mutilated victory", the fear of social unrest and the rejection of revolutionary, republican and Marxist ideology.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The liberal political system and part of the aristocracy chose to erect fascism as a bulwark against, in their way of seeing, these dangers.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In October 1922, the nomination of Benito Mussolini as prime minister by King Victor Emmanuel III, following the march on Rome, paved the way for the establishment of the dictatorship.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The Albertine Statute was progressively emptied of its content.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Parliament was subject to the will of the new government.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On 27 June 1924, 127 deputies left Parliament and retreated to the Aventine Hill, a clumsy maneuver which, in effect, left the field open to the fascists.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] They then had the fate of Italy in their hands for two decades.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Not only did Victor Emmanuel III appeal to Mussolini to form the government in 1922 and allow him to proceed with the domestication of Parliament, but he did not even draw the consequences of the assassination of Giacomo Matteotti in 1924.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] He accepted the title of emperor in 1936 at the end of Second Italo-Ethiopian War, then the alliance with Nazi Germany and Italy's entry into World War II on 10 June 1940.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] With the implementation of fascist laws (Royal Decree of 6 November 1926), all political parties operating on Italian territory were dissolved, with the exception of the National Fascist Party.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Some of these parties expatriated and reconstituted themselves abroad, especially in France.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Some movements remained outside, including the Italian Communist Party, the popular Catholic movement and other liberal movements.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] This coalition dissolved on 5 May 1934 and, in August of the same year, the pact of unity of action was signed between the Italian Socialist Party and the Italian Communist Party.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In the meantime, in Italy, clandestine anti-fascist nuclei were formed, in particular in Milan with Ferruccio Parri and in Florence with Riccardo Bauer.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Under the impetus of these groups, the Action Party, Mazzini's former republican party, was re-established.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Between the end of 1942 and the beginning of 1943, Alcide De Gasperi wrote *The reconstructive ideas of Christian Democracy*, which laid the foundations of the new Catholic-inspired party, the Christian Democracy.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] It brought together the veterans of Luigi Sturzo's Italian People's Party and the young people of Catholic associations, in particular of the University Federation.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On 10 July 1943, the Allies landed in Sicily in Operation Husky.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On 25 July 1943, Victor Emmanuel III revoked Mussolini's mandate as prime minister and had him arrested, entrusting the government to Marshal Pietro Badoglio.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The new government contacted the Allies to reach an armistice.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] When the Armistice of Cassibile was announced on 8 September 1943, the Germans reacted by placing under their control all the part of Italian territory that still escaped the Allied advance and by disarming the Italian Royal Army.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Victor Emmanuel III and Badoglio's government fled Rome and reached Brindisi, in southern Italy.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In these dramatic circumstances, in the two territories the civil administration gave way to a military and police administration.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] However, the parties that existed before fascism were reconstituted, alongside new political parties.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On 9 September 1943, in Rome (still occupied by the Germans), a National Liberation Committee (CLN) was created, which brought together the parties and movements opposed to fascism and German occupation.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] It was made up of representatives of the Italian Communist Party, members of the Action Party, Christian Democrats, liberals, socialists and progressive democrats.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The patriotic war of liberation led by the National Liberation Committee was also, for a significant part of its supporters, a war of social liberation, a war against a collaborationist elite.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] However, the Americans and English, anxious to prepare for the post-war period, facilitated the entry into German-occupied territory of Italian democratic and republican activists aimed at counterbalancing the communist influence in the leadership of the National Liberation Committee.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] This was the case, for example, of Leo Valiani, future member of the triumvirate responsible for the partisan insurrection in Piedmont and Lombardy.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On 31 March 1944, in Salerno, Palmiro Togliatti, general secretary of the Italian Communist Party, called for the formation of a government of national unity and no longer required the king's abdication as a prerequisite.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] This declaration pushed the parties of the National Liberation Committee to rally around a compromise drawn up by Enrico De Nicola, president of the Chamber of Deputies until 1924, by Benedetto Croce of the liberal party and by the king's entourage.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] As foreseen in this agreement, upon the liberation of Rome, on 4 June 1944, Victor Emmanuel III proclaimed his son Umberto lieutenant general of the kingdom, and the parties took political control of the nation, even if the war continued, stabilizing on the front on the Gothic line until April 1945.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] From June 1944 to December 1945, three provisional coalition governments followed one another.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The first was led by Ivanoe Bonomi, of the Labour Democratic Party.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] His government included the anti-fascist liberals Carlo Sforza and Benedetto Croce, as well as Palmiro Togliatti.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Although temporarily put aside, the question of Italian institutions remained one of the main open political questions.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Most of the forces supporting the National Liberation Committee were openly republicans and believed that the monarchy, in particular Victor Emmanuel III, had had a responsibility in the success of the fascist movement.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The final agreement between the parties was to ask that at the end of the war, as soon as conditions were favourable, the calling of elections, an institutional referendum and the formation of a constituent assembly.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Until then, on 31 January 1945, the Council of Ministers, chaired by Ivanoe Bonomi, issued a decree which recognized women's right to vote.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Universal suffrage was thus recognized, after the vain attempts made in 1881 and 1907 by women of the various parties.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The Bonomi governments (II then III) were succeeded by the Parri government in June 1945, then by the First De Gasperi government in December 1945.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The question of the future form of the state, monarchy or republic, absorbed the minds of political circles.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The majority of Christian Democratic activists, especially young people, increasingly distanced themselves from the monarchy.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] During the local meetings of the leaders of this party, in Rome and Milan, motions were presented aimed at making official a political line favorable to a democratic republic.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The central political office tried to curb these pressures and maintain an intermediate position.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On 16 March 1946, Prince Umberto decreed, as expected in 1944, that the question of the institutional form of the state would be decided by a referendum organized simultaneously with the election of a constituent assembly.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The Supreme Court of Cassation was responsible for examining the appeals.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Its role was to be limited to observing the progress of voting operations and consolidating the bulletins issued by the offices that communicated the results in each constituency.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The counting of the ballots of the candidates for the constituent assembly had to precede that of the referendum.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] If the monarchy had won, it would have been the Constituent Assembly that would have had to choose the head of state.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Wanted by the Allies to verify that the conditions existed for voting in a country torn apart by the civil war only a few months earlier, partial municipal and provincial elections were held in March and April 1946 in half of the Italian municipalities and provinces.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] These elections, which mainly involved left-wing cities, brought out three parties, with a clear advantage for the Christian Democrats, led by Alcide De Gasperi, which exceeded the sum of votes cast for the Italian Communist Party and the Italian Socialist Party.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] After these administrative elections, the monarchists, already worried about the outcome of the referendum, became even more discouraged.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] But a political event changed the situation during the referendum campaign.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] A month before the referendum, Victor Emmanuel III abdicated in favor of his son Umberto, who was proclaimed king and took the name Umberto II.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The act of abdication, drawn up privately, is dated 9 May 1946.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] This abdication was desired by the monarchists, since the crown prince was less compromised than his father in Mussolini's rise to power and in coexistence with the fascist forces.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] It is also possible that the command of the allied forces present on Italian territory encouraged the sovereign to abdicate in favor of his son.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The former king immediately left Italy for Alexandria in Egypt.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Umberto II confirmed his promise to respect the popular decision regarding the referendum.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The representatives of the parties in favor of the Republic protested, arguing the assumption of royal powers by the lieutenant general conflicted with an article of the legislative decree of 16 March 1946 that aimed at guaranteeing institutional stability before the announcement of the results.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] For observers, the gap between republicans and monarchists was narrowing, which increased tension in the final phase of the electoral campaign.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In fact, some scuffles broke out between activists of the two sides in the tense climate.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The vote for the choice between monarchy or republic took place on 2 June and on the morning of 3 June 1946.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] After the transfer of the electoral cards from all of Italy and the minutes of the 31 constituencies to Rome, the results were expected on 8 June.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On 10 June, the still provisional results were announced, and the final ones were communicated later due to missing data in some polling stations and after the examination of numerous appeals regarding the contested referendum ballots.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In fact, 21,000 disputes occurred over the referendum ballots, most of which were quickly resolved.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] However, the period of uncertainty between the end of the vote and the final official announcement of the results only strengthened tensions in the country.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In the city of Naples, in Apulia, in Calabria and in Sicily, the monarchists carried out protest demonstrations, sometimes violent.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On 7 June, a monarchist student, soon transformed into a martyr, was killed.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] One of the complaints submitted to the Supreme Court of Cassation is particularly delicate.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] This controversy was over the definition of "majority".
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The monarchists believed that it was necessary to take into account not the majority of votes cast, but the "majority of electors", as an article of the electoral law provided.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The public prosecutor of the Supreme Court of Cassation, Massimo Pilotti, deemed this appeal admissible.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In his indictment Pilotti believed that the spirit and letter of the decrees as well as jurisprudence provide for the counting of voters, without excluding blank or invalid ballots.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] But the Supreme Court of Cassation ruled against him, with 12 votes against to 7.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On the one hand, it was believed that the vote, as a legal act, manifested a will and that the blank or null vote could be assimilated to the absence of expression of will.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The Supreme Court of Cassation also identified another decree which specified that only "validly cast" votes should be preserved.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The Supreme Court of Cassation finally announced that no law or decree dealt with the need for an absolute majority.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The final results were announced on 18 June 1946.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Voter turnout was 89%, with 54% of the votes cast for the republic and 46% for the monarchy.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The analysis of the data by region showed an Italy practically divided in two: in the north the republic won with 66% of the votes cast, and the monarchy in the south with 64% of the votes.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] However, some voters were unable to vote.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Before the closure of the electoral lists in April 1945, many Italian soldiers were still outside the national territory, in detention or internment camps abroad.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] These provinces, however, were all located in the north of the country, an area where the Republican vote obtained a fairly large majority.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The conservative, rural *Mezzogiorno* (southern Italy) region voted solidly for the monarchy (63.8%) while the more urbanised and industrialised *Nord* (northern Italy) voted equally firmly for a republic (66.2%).
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The referendum was not held in the Julian March, in the province of Zara or the province of Bolzano, which were still under occupation by Allied forces pending a final settlement of the status of the territories.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] At first glance, the referendum seemed to simply divide Italy in two, between North and South, but the situation was more complex.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] For example, the districts located to the north of Rome gave the majority to the republic, while those located to the south chose the monarchy.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The electoral college of Rome was very divided and gave a slight majority to the choice of the monarchic regime.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The Republican choice turned into a plebiscite, with over 80% of the votes cast in the electoral college of Bologna, and even more in that of Trento.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In the South, however, the monarchist choice reached nearly 80% in the college of Naples.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] But, in other regions, the vote was very fragmented.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] There was not a total break with the past, but an interference between the two possible choices, which was expressed everywhere.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The occupation of the North by the German forces and the period of the Italian Civil War, with the fascist forces, undoubtedly favored an increase in the importance of the socialist and communist parties in this region, which were republican in tendency.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] During these dark years, the populations concerned placed part of their hopes in dreams of revolution, or at least of change.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The South, not having experienced this situation and having welcomed King Victor Emmanuel III and his government, was perhaps more wary of these parties and placed its trust in the monarchic regime, preferring continuity to the "leap into the unknown" represented by the republican form.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Furthermore, the clientelism prevalent in the South favored a vote that tended to be conservative, and therefore monarchist.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Some analysts also cite the influence of the Catholic Church or the Catholic press.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Other authors have highlighted more structural factors, such as differences in family organization or production by region.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Thus Carlo Bacetti compared, in Tuscany, the importance of metayage in the organization of work on the land, and the weight of the Communist Party in this region, which had republican tendencies.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] At the same time, republican demonstrations took place in many cities.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The Milanese newspaper, *Corriere della Sera*, on Tuesday 11 June, ran the headline: "The Italian Republic is born".
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] *La Stampa*, a Turin daily newspaper, declared more soberly: "The government confirms the victory of the republicans", and completed its coverage by asking: "the question is whether the republic has been proclaimed or not".
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In Naples, a city with a population largely supportive of the monarchy, an incident occurred on 11 June.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] A procession of supporters of the monarchy advanced towards the municipal buildings and then changed objective and headed towards the headquarters of the Italian Communist Party.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The crowd saw a red flag, but also a tricolor flag from which the royal coat of arms had been cut.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Despite the presence of armored vehicles, the demonstrators attempted to storm the communist party headquarters.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Protesters and law enforcement officers exchange gunfire.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] According to the prefect's report, the demonstrators shot first.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In any case the response was deadly, with machine gun fire.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] There were nine deaths among royalist demonstrators and a large number of injuries.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Calm returned to the city only on 13 June.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On the night of 12 June, the government met at Alcide De Gasperi's invitation.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The Prime Minister received a written communication from the King, in which he said he was ready to respect the verdict of the electors' vote, but adding that he would await the final declaration of the Supreme Court of Cassation.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The letter and the protests of the monarchists, like the bloody events of the day before in Naples, as well as the new demonstrations announced by the monarchists worried the ministers.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The Prime Minister collected all the votes of the government members, with the exception of the liberal minister Leone Cattani.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Although some members of his entourage encouraged him to oppose this decision, the king, informed, decided to leave the country the following day, thus making a peaceful transfer of power possible, not without having denounced De Gasperi's "revolutionary gesture".
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] He went into exile in Cascais, Portugal.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On the same day as the former king's departure, the flag of Italy with the Savoy coat of arms in the centre was lowered from the Quirinal Palace.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The Italian flag was modified with the decree of the president of the Council of Ministers No.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Compared to the monarchic banner, the Savoy coat of arms was eliminated.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The Republican tricolour was then officially and solemnly delivered to the Italian military corps on 4 November 1947 on the occasion of National Unity and Armed Forces Day.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The universally adopted ratio is 2:3, while the war flag is squared (1:1).
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Each *comune* also has a *gonfalone* bearing its coat of arms.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On 27 May 1949, a law was passed that described and regulated the way the flag was displayed outside public buildings and during national holidays.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] After the birth of the Italian Republic, "La leggenda del Piave" was temporarily chosen as the provisional national anthem, which replaced "Marcia Reale", the national anthem of the Kingdom of Italy.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The political class of the time then approved the proposal of the War Minister Cipriano Facchinetti, who foresaw the adoption of "Il Canto degli Italiani" as a provisional anthem of the State.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] "Il Canto degli Italiani" was therefore chosen, on 12 October 1946, as the provisional national anthem, a role that it later preserved while remaining the de facto anthem of the Italian Republic.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Over the decades there were several unsuccessful attempts to make it the official national anthem, until it finally gained official status on 4 December 2017.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On 18 June 1946 at 6 pm, in the Sala della Lupa of Palazzo Montecitorio in Rome, the Supreme Court of Cassation proceeded to proclaim the results of the referendum, without accompanying this formalization with reservations as it had done previously.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In the first session of the Constituent Assembly, on 28 June 1946, Enrico De Nicola was elected provisional head of the State, in the first round with 396 votes out of 501.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In addition to his personal qualities, the choice of a man born in Naples and long monarchic history, it was a sign of pacification and union towards the populations of southern Italy, in this accelerated transition towards the Republic.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] He was initially only provisional head of state and not president of Italy, since the latter did not yet have a constitution.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Alcide De Gasperi resigned and then regained the task of forming a new government, thus becoming the last Prime Minister of the monarchic era and the first of republican Italy.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On 1 January 1948, the Republican Constitution came into force, the content of which was discussed within the Constituent Assembly.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] It proclaims in particular that "Italy is a democratic republic founded on labour" and that "the former kings of the House of Savoy, their wives and their male descendants are prohibited from entering and staying in the national territory".
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Enrico De Nicola then assumed the title of President of Italy.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The validity of the provision that prohibited the entry in Italy of some members of the House of Savoy ceased with the entry into force of the Constitutional Law of 23 October 2002, No.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] 1, after a debate in parliament and in the country that lasted many years and Vittorio Emanuele, Prince of Naples, son of King Umberto II, was able to enter Italy with his family already in the following December for a short visit.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The former queen Marie-José had already been authorized to return to Italy in 1987 since, with the death of her husband Umberto II and having become a widow, her status as "spouse" was recognized as having ceased.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The photo, which later became a "symbol" of the celebrations for the outcome of the referendum, portrays the face of a young woman emerging from a copy of *Il Corriere della Sera* of 6 June 1946 with the title «*È nata la Repubblica Italiana*» ("The Italian Republic is born").
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The symbolic photo of the birth of the Republic was taken by Federico Patellani for the weekly *Tempo* (n.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] 22, 15–22 June 1946) as part of a photo shoot celebrating the Republic and the new role of women; it was also featured on the front page of the *Il Corriere della Sera* itself and was later reused in many campaigns and posters.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Only in 2016 was the woman identified as Anna Iberti (1922–1997).
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] After the playing of the National Anthem *Il Canto degli Italiani*, the Frecce Tricolori cross the skies of Rome.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] It is tradition, for the members of the Italian government and for the presidents of the two chambers of parliament, to have pinned on their jacket, during the whole ceremony, an Italian tricolor cockade.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Following the anthem, the military parade begins, which the ground columns of military personnel saluting the President with eyes left or right with their colours dipped as they march past the dais.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Mobile column crew contingent colour guards perform the salute in a like manner.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The military parade also includes some military delegations from the United Nations, NATO, the European Union and representatives of multinational departments with an Italian component.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On the holiday, at the Quirinale Palace, the Changing of the Guard with the Corazzieri Regiment and the Fanfare of the Carabinieri Cavalry Regiment in high uniform is carried out in solemn form.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] This solemn rite is only performed on two other occasions, during the celebrations of the Tricolour Day (7 January) and the National Unity and Armed Forces Day (4 November).
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Official ceremonies are held throughout the national territory.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Among them are the traditional receptions organized by each prefecture for the local authorities, which are preceded by solemn public demonstrations with reduced military parades that have been reviewed by the prefect in his capacity as the highest governmental authority in the province.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Similar ceremonies are also organized by the Regions and Municipalities.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] All over the world, Italian embassies organize ceremonies to which the Heads of State of the host country are invited.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Greetings from the other Heads of State reach the President of Italy from all over the world.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The **1948 Palestine war** (30 November 1947 – 10 March 1949) was fought in the territory of what had been, at the start of the war, British-ruled Mandatory Palestine.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] During the war, Zionist forces conquered about 78% of the former territory of the mandate, causing the expulsion and flight of over 700,000 Palestinians.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Transjordan took control of the territory west of the Jordan River and Egypt occupied the coastal territory around Gaza.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The war formally ended with the 1949 Armistice Agreements, which established the Green Line *de facto* borders of the State of Israel, the West Bank, and the Gaza Strip.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] It was the first war of the Israeli–Palestinian conflict and the broader Arab–Israeli conflict.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The war had two main phases, the first being the 1947–1948 civil war, which began on 30 November 1947, a day after the United Nations voted to adopt the Partition Plan for Palestine, which planned for the division of the territory into Jewish and Arab sovereign states.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] During this period, the British still maintained a declining rule over Palestine and occasionally intervened in the violence.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Initially on the defensive, the Zionist forces switched to the offensive in April 1948.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] In anticipation of an invasion by Arab armies, they enacted Plan Dalet, an operation aimed at securing territory for the establishment of a Jewish state.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The second phase of the war began on 14 May 1948, with the declaration of the establishment of the State of Israel and the termination of the British Mandate at midnight.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The following morning, the surrounding Arab armies invaded Palestine, beginning the 1948 Arab–Israeli War.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The Egyptians advanced in the south-east while the Jordanian Arab Legion and Iraqi forces captured the central highlands.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Syria and Lebanon fought against the Israeli forces in the north.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The newly formed Israel Defense Forces managed to halt the Arab forces and in the following months began pushing them back and capturing territory.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] During the war, massacres and acts of terror were conducted by both sides.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] A campaign of massacres and violence against the Arab population, such as occurred at Lydda and Ramle and the Battle of Haifa, led to the expulsion and flight of over 700,000 Palestinians, with most of their urban areas being depopulated and destroyed.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] This violence and dispossession is remembered by Palestinians as the Nakba (Arabic for "the catastrophe") and resulted in the beginning of the Palestinian refugee problem.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Hundreds of thousands of Jews fled or were expelled from Arab states in the three years following the Arab defeat in the war, over 260,000 of which settled in Israel.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Zionism formed in Europe as the national movement of the Jewish people.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] It sought to reestablish Jewish statehood in the ancient homeland.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The first wave of Zionist immigration, dubbed the First Aliyah, lasted from 1882 to 1903.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Some 30,000 Jews, mostly from the Russian Empire, reached Ottoman Palestine.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] They were driven both by the Zionist idea and by the wave of antisemitism in Europe, especially in the Russian Empire, which came in the form of brutal pogroms.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] They wanted to establish Jewish agricultural settlements and a Jewish majority in the land that would allow them to gain statehood.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The Arab inhabitants of Ottoman Palestine who saw the Zionist Jews of the first aliyah settle next to them were not associated with a national movement at the end of the 19th century.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Historically, Palestine had never been administered or recognized as a distinct province by any of its Muslim rulers.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Starting in 1882, the Ottomans issued a stream of "restrictive orders" against Jewish settlement and land purchases in Palestine.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] However, as a result of its perceived insignificance and the inefficiency of Ottoman bureaucracies, these restrictions had little effect.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Until the 1910s, Zionists encountered little violence, as the Arabs lacked political awareness and were disorganized.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Between 1909 and 1914, this changed, as Arabs killed 12 Jewish settlement guards and Arab nationalism, and opposition to the Zionist enterprise, increased.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] In 1911, Arabs attempted to thwart the establishment of a Jewish settlement in the Jezreel Valley, and the dispute resulted in the death of one Arab man and a Jewish guard.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The Arabs called the Jews the "new Crusaders", and anti-Zionist (and, occasionally, anti-Semitic) rhetoric flourished.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] During the war, Palestine served as the frontline between the Ottoman Empire and the British Empire in Egypt.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The war briefly halted Jewish-Arab friction.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The British invaded the land in 1915 and 1916 after two unsuccessful Ottoman attacks on Sinai.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] They were assisted by the Arab tribes in Hejaz, led by the Hashemites, and promised them sovereignty over the Arab areas of the Ottoman Empire.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Palestine was excluded from the promise, initially intended to be a joint British-French domain.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Zionist lobbying, led by Chaim Weizmann, played a significant role, along with religious and humanitarian motivations.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The fact that the Arabs of Palestine supported the Ottoman fight against the Allied Powers also contributed.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Additionally, the British believed that a British-backed state would help defend the Suez Canal.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] At that time, the Arab Hashemites did not seem opposed to Jewish rule over Palestine.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] After World War I, the League of Nations granted Britain the Mandate for Palestine, which required it to implement the Balfour Declaration.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] As the numbers and strength of the Yishuv (the Jewish community in Palestine) grew, tensions between the Jewish and Arab communities deepened.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Significant bouts of violence happened during the 1920 Jerusalem Riots, as well as in 1921 and 1929.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] In addition to the emerging Palestinian Arab nationalism, the violence also drew on religious inspirations, such as the accusation that the Jews intended to take over the Temple Mount.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Despite Arab opposition to Jewish immigration, leading Palestinian families continued to sell land to Zionists throughout the period.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] At least one quarter of members of the Palestinian Arab Executive benefited financially from such purchases, including the mayor of Jerusalem and the al-Husayni family.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The Zionist leaders intermittently attempted to reach a compromise with the Arabs, but none proved possible.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The peasant-led 1936–1939 Arab revolt in Palestine broke out in the context of increased Jewish migration to Palestine and the plight of the rural native *fallāḥīn*.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] It sparked following the murder of three Jewish drivers on April 15, 1936, whose funeral led rapidly spreading disturbances.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The revolt began with a general strike among Palestinian Arabs on April 19, 1936, which escalated into intercommunal violence.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The brutal suppression of the revolt by the British significantly weakened the Palestinian Arabs in advance of the 1948 war.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Particularly after the White Paper of 1939, the Zionist paramilitary organizations Irgun, Lehi, and Haganah carried out a campaign of acts of terror and sabotage against British rule.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Among these attacks was the 1946 King David Hotel bombing carried out by the Irgun which killed 91 people.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Following World War II, the surrounding Arab states were emerging from mandatory rule.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Transjordan, under the Hashemite ruler Abdullah I, gained independence from Britain in 1946 and was called Jordan in 1949, but remained under heavy British influence.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Egypt gained nominal independence in 1922, but Britain continued to exert a strong influence on it until the Anglo-Egyptian Treaty of 1936 limited Britain's presence to a garrison of troops on the Suez Canal until 1945.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Lebanon became an independent state in 1943, but French troops did not withdraw until 1946, the same year Syria won its independence from France.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] In 1945, at British prompting, Egypt, Iraq, Lebanon, Saudi Arabia, Syria, Transjordan, and Yemen formed the Arab League to coordinate policy among the Arab states.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Iraq and Transjordan coordinated closely, signing a mutual defence treaty, while Egypt, Syria, and Saudi Arabia feared that Transjordan would annex part or all of Palestine and use it as a stepping stone to attack or undermine Syria, Lebanon, and the Hijaz.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] This was an attempt to resolve the Arab-Jewish conflict by partitioning Palestine into "Independent Arab and Jewish States and the Special International Regime for the City of Jerusalem".
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Each state would comprise three major sections; the Arab state would also have an enclave in Jaffa, which had an Arab-majority population and provided the Arab state with a port on the Mediterranean.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] With about 32% of the population, the Jews were allocated 56% of the territory (most of it the Negev desert).
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The Palestinian Arabs were allocated 42% of the land, which had a population of 818,000 Palestinian Arabs and 10,000 Jews.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] In consideration of its religious significance, the Jerusalem area, including Bethlehem, with 100,000 Jews and an equal number of Palestinian Arabs, was to become a *corpus separatum*, to be administered by the UN.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The residents in the UN-administered territory were given the right to choose to be citizens of either of the new states.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The Jewish leadership accepted the partition plan as "the indispensable minimum", glad to gain international recognition but sorry that they did not receive more.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The representatives of the Palestinian Arabs and the Arab League firmly opposed the UN action and rejected its authority in the matter, arguing that the partition plan was unfair to the Arabs because of the population balance at that time.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] According to the Israeli historian Benny Morris, the Arabs rejected the partition, not because it was supposedly unfair, but because their leaders rejected any form of partition.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] They held "that the rule of Palestine should revert to its inhabitants, in accordance with the provisions of ... the Charter of the United Nations".
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] According to Article 73b of the Charter, the UN should develop self-government of the peoples in a territory under its administration.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] In the immediate aftermath of the UN's approval of the partition plan, explosions of joy in the Jewish community were counterbalanced by discontent in the Arab community.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Soon after, violence broke out and became more prevalent.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Murders, reprisals, and counter-reprisals came fast upon each other, resulting in dozens killed on both sides.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The sanguinary impasse persisted as no force intervened to put a stop to the escalating violence.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The first phase of the war took place from the United Nations General Assembly vote for the Partition Plan for Palestine on 29 November 1947 until the termination of the British Mandate and Israeli proclamation of statehood on 14 May 1948.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] During this period the Jewish and Arab communities of the British Mandate clashed, while the British organised their withdrawal and intervened only occasionally.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] In the first two months of the Civil War, around 1,000 people were killed and 2,000 injured, and by the end of March, the figure had risen to 2,000 dead and 4,000 wounded.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] These figures correspond to an average of more than 100 deaths and 200 casualties per week in a population of 2,000,000.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] From January onwards, operations became increasingly militarised.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] A number of Arab Liberation Army regiments infiltrated Palestine, each active in a variety of distinct sectors around the coastal towns.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] They consolidated their presence in Galilee and Samaria.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The Army of the Holy War, under Abd al-Qadir al-Husayni's command, came from Egypt with several hundred men.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Having recruited a few thousand volunteers, al-Husayni organised the blockade of the 100,000 Jewish residents of Jerusalem.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] To counter this, the Yishuv authorities tried to supply the city with convoys of up to 100 armoured vehicles, but the operation became more and more impractical as the number of casualties in the relief convoys surged.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] By March, al-Husayni's tactic had paid off.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Almost all of Haganah's armoured vehicles had been destroyed, the blockade was in full operation, and hundreds of Haganah members who had tried to bring supplies into the city were killed.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The situation for those in the Jewish settlements in the highly isolated Negev and North of Galilee was more critical.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] This caused the US to withdraw its support for the Partition Plan, and the Arab League began to believe that the Palestinian Arabs, reinforced by the Arab Liberation Army, could end the partition.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The British decided on 7 February 1948 to support Transjordan's annexation of the Arab part of Palestine.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] While the Jewish population was ordered to hold their ground everywhere at all costs, the Arab population was disrupted by general conditions of insecurity.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Up to 100,000 Arabs from the urban upper and middle classes in Haifa, Jaffa and Jerusalem, or Jewish-dominated areas, evacuated abroad or to Arab centres to the east.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] David Ben-Gurion ordered Yigal Yadin to plan for the announced intervention of the Arab states.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The result of his analysis was Plan Dalet, which was put in place at the start of April, and which marked the war's second phase, in which the Haganah took the offensive.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The first operation, Nachshon, was directed at lifting the blockade on Jerusalem.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] In the last week of March, 136 supply trucks had tried to reach Jerusalem; only 41 had made it.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The Arab attacks on communications and roads had intensified.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The convoys' failure and the loss of Jewish armoured vehicles had shaken the Yishuv leaders' confidence.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The city's food and water supply was cut off.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Jerusalem was on the verge of starvation in May, both food and water rationing had been introduced.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] During this time, paramilitary groups Irgun and Lehi, supported by the Haganah and Palmach, perpetrated the Deir Yassin massacre, killing at least 107 Arab villagers, including women and children, and expelled the rest of the village's residents (approximately 750 people).
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The event was widely publicized and had a deep effect on the Arab population's morale, greatly contributing to the Palestinian expulsion and flight.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The Hadassah medical convoy massacre was conducted by Arab forces as retaliation for Deir Yassin.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] 79 Jews were killed in the attack which led to a further deterioration of Jewish-Arab relations.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] From April 4–15, the first large-scale operation of the Arab Liberation Army ended in a debacle, as they were roundly defeated at Mishmar HaEmek.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Their Druze allies left them through defection.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] As part of Plan Dalet, the Haganah, Palmach and Irgun captured the urban centers of Tiberias, Haifa (See: Battle of Haifa), Safed, Beisan, Jaffa, and Acre, violently expelling more than 250,000 Palestinian Arabs.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The British had essentially withdrawn their troops.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The situation pushed the neighbouring Arab states to intervene, but their preparation was not completed, and they could not assemble sufficient forces to turn the tide of the war.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The majority of Palestinian Arab hopes lay with the Arab Legion of Transjordan's monarch, King Abdullah I.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] However Abdullah did not intend to create a Palestinian state, but hoped to annex much of Eastern Palestine.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Playing both sides, he was in contact with both the Israelis and the Arab League.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Preparing for Arab intervention from neighbouring states, Haganah successfully launched Operations Yiftah and Ben-'Ami to secure the Jewish settlements of Galilee, and Operation Kilshon.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] This created an Israeli-controlled front around Jerusalem.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The inconclusive meeting between Golda Meir and Abdullah I, followed by the Kfar Etzion massacre on 13 May by the Arab Legion, led to predictions that the battle for Jerusalem would be merciless.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Israeli historians Benny Morris and Benjamin Kedar revealed that during the 1948 war, Israel conducted a biological warfare operation codenamed *Cast Thy Bread*, using typhoid bacteria to contaminate wells in Arab areas to prevent reentry and deter advancing Arab forces.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] On 14 May 1948, the day before the expiration of the British Mandate, David Ben-Gurion declared the establishment of a Jewish state in Eretz Israel, to be known as the State of Israel.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The Palestinians' Arab Higher Committee rejected the Partition Resolution and any kind of Jewish state and refused to negotiate with "the Zionist Project".
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Over the next few days, contingents of four of the seven countries of the Arab League at that time, Egypt, Iraq, Transjordan, and Syria, invaded the former British Mandate of Palestine and fought the Israelis.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] They were supported by the Arab Liberation Army, Muslim Brotherhood contingents, and corps of volunteers from Saudi Arabia, Lebanon and Yemen.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The Arab armies launched a simultaneous offensive on all fronts: Egyptian forces invaded from the south, Jordanian and Iraqi forces from the east, and Syrian forces invaded from the north.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Cooperation among the various Arab armies was poor.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The UN declared a truce on 29 May, which began on 11 June and lasted 28 days.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The ceasefire was overseen by UN mediator Folke Bernadotte and a team of UN Observers, army officers from Belgium, United States, Sweden and France.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Bernadotte was voted in by the General Assembly to "assure the safety of the holy places, to safeguard the well being of the population, and to promote 'a peaceful adjustment of the future situation of Palestine'".
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] He spoke of "peace by Christmas" but saw that the Arab world had continued to reject the existence of a Jewish state, whatever its borders.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] An arms embargo was declared with the intention that neither side would make gains from the truce.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Neither side respected the truce; both found ways around the restrictions.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Both the Israelis and the Arabs used this time to improve their positions, a direct violation of the terms of the ceasefire.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] "The Arabs violated the truce by reinforcing their lines with fresh units (including six companies of Sudanese regulars, a Saudi battalion and contingents from Yemen and Morocco) and by preventing supplies from reaching isolated Israeli settlements; occasionally, they opened fire along the lines".
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The Israeli Defense Forces acquired weapons from Czechoslovakia in contravention to the terms of the truce, improving the training of its forces, and reorganising the army.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Yitzhak Rabin, an IDF commander who would later become Israel's fifth prime minister, said, "[w]ithout the arms from Czechoslovakia... it is very doubtful whether we would have been able to conduct the war".
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] As well as violating the arms and personnel embargo, both sides sent fresh units to the front.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Israel's army increased its manpower from approximately 30,000 or 35,000 men to almost 65,000 during the truce and its arms supply to "more than twenty-five thousand rifles, five thousand machine guns, and more than fifty million bullets".
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] As the truce began, a British officer stationed in Haifa said the four-week-long truce "would certainly be exploited by the Jews to continue military training and reorganization while the Arabs would waste [them] feuding over the future divisions of the spoils".
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] On 7 July, the day before the truce expired, Egyptian forces under General Muhammad Naguib renewed the war by attacking Negba.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Israeli forces launched a simultaneous offensive on all three fronts: Dani, Dekel, and Kedem.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The fighting was dominated by large-scale Israeli offensives and a defensive Arab posture and continued for ten days until the UN Security Council issued the Second Truce on 18 July.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Israeli Operation Dani resulted in the expulsion from Lydda and Ramle of 60,000 Palestinian residents.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] According to Benny Morris, in Ben-Gurion's view, Ramlah and Lydda constituted a special danger because their proximity might encourage cooperation between the Egyptian army, which had started its attack on Kibbutz Negbah, and the Arab Legion, which had taken the Lydda police station.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Widespread looting took place during these operations, and about 100,000 Palestinians became refugees.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] In Operation Dekel, Nazareth was captured on 16 July.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] In Operation Brosh, Israel tried and failed to drive the Syrian army out of northeastern Galilee.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] By the time the second truce took effect at 19:00 18 July, Israel had taken the lower Galilee from Haifa Bay to the Sea of Galilee.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] With smuggled Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress planes acquired in violation of the international arms embargo, Israel bombed a residential neighborhood in Cairo on July 15.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] At 19:00 on 18 July, the second truce of the conflict went into effect after intense diplomatic efforts by the UN.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] On 16 September, a new partition plan for Palestine was proposed but it was rejected by both sides.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] During the truce, the Egyptians regularly blocked the passage of supply convoys to the beleaguered northern Negev settlements by firing on them, contrary to the truce terms.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] On 15 October, they attacked another supply convoy, and the already planned Operation Yoav was launched.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Its goal was to drive a wedge between the Egyptian forces along the coast and the Beersheba-Hebron-Jerusalem road, and to open the road to the encircled Negev settlements.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Yoav was headed by Southern Front commander Yigal Allon.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The operation was a success, shattering the Egyptian army ranks and forcing Egyptian forces to retreat from the northern Negev, Beersheba, and Ashdod.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Meanwhile, on 19 October, Operation Ha-Har commenced operations in the Jerusalem Corridor.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] On 22 October, the third truce went into effect.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Before dawn on 22 October, in defiance of the UN Security Council ceasefire order, ALA units stormed the IDF hilltop position of Sheikh Abd, overlooking Kibbutz Manara.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Ben-Gurion initially rejected Moshe Carmel's demand to launch a major counteroffensive.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] He was wary of antagonising the United Nations on the heels of its ceasefire order.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] During 24–25 October, ALA troops regularly sniped at Manara and traffic along the main road.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] In contacts with UN observers, Fawzi al-Qawuqji demanded that Israel evacuate neighbouring Kibbutz Yiftah and thin out its forces in Manara.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The IDF demanded the ALA's withdrawal from the captured positions and, after a "no" from al-Qawuqji, informed the UN that it felt free to do as it pleased.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] On 24 October, the IDF launched Operation Hiram and captured the entire upper Galilee, originally attributed to the Arab state by the Partition Plan.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] At the end of the month, Israel had captured the whole Galilee and had advanced 5 miles (8.0 km) into Lebanon to the Litani River.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] On 22 December, large IDF forces started Operation Horev.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Its objective was to encircle the Egyptian Army in the Gaza Strip and force the Egyptians to end the war.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The operation was a decisive Israeli victory, and Israeli raids into the Nitzana area and the Sinai Peninsula forced the Egyptian army into the Gaza Strip, where it was surrounded.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Israeli forces withdrew from Sinai and Gaza under international pressure and after the British threatened to intervene against Israel.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The Egyptian government announced on 6 January 1949 that it was willing to enter armistice negotiations.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Allon persuaded Ben-Gurion to continue as planned, but Ben-Gurion told him: "Do you know the value of peace talks with Egypt?
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] After all, that is our great dream!" He was sure that Transjordan and the other Arab states would follow suit.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] On 7 January 1949, a truce was achieved.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] On 5 March, Israel launched Operation Uvda; by 10 March, the Israelis reached Umm Rashrash (where Eilat was built later) and took it without a battle.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The Negev Brigade and Golani Brigade took part in the operation.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] They raised a hand-made flag ("The Ink Flag") and claimed Umm Rashrash for Israel.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] In 1949, Israel signed separate armistices with Egypt on 24 February, Lebanon on 23 March, Transjordan on 3 April, and Syria on 20 July.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The armistice lines saw Israel holding about 78% of Mandatory Palestine (as it stood after the independence of Transjordan in 1946), 22% more than the UN Partition Plan had allocated.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] These ceasefire lines were known afterwards as the "Green Line".
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The Gaza Strip and the West Bank were occupied by Egypt and Transjordan, respectively.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The United Nations Truce Supervision Organization and Mixed Armistice Commissions were set up to monitor ceasefires, supervise the armistice agreements, to prevent isolated incidents from escalating, and assist other UN peacekeeping operations in the region.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Israel lost 6,373 people, about 1% of its population, in the war.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] About 4,000 were soldiers and the rest were civilians.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The exact number of Arab losses is unknown but is estimated at between 4,000 for Egypt (2,000), Jordan and Syria (1,000 each) and 15,000.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] During the 1947–48 Civil War in Mandatory Palestine and the 1948 Arab–Israeli War that followed, around 700,000 Palestinian Arabs fled or were expelled.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] In 1951, the UN Conciliation Commission for Palestine estimated that the number of Palestinian refugees displaced from Israel was 711,000.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] This number did not include displaced Palestinians inside Israeli-held territory.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The list of villages depopulated during the Arab–Israeli conflict includes more than 400 Arab villages.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] It also includes about ten Jewish villages and neighbourhoods, resulting in no Jews left in or being able to return to the Arab-controlled territory.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The causes of the 1948 Palestinian exodus are a controversial topic among historians.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The Palestinian refugee problem and the debate around the right of their return are also major issues of the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Palestinians have staged annual demonstrations and protests on 15 May of each year.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] During the 1948 Arab–Israeli War, around 10,000 Jews were forced to evacuate their homes in Palestine or Israel.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The war indirectly resulted in the Jewish exodus from Arab and Muslim lands.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Largely because of the war between Jews and Arabs in Palestine, hundreds of thousands of Jews who lived in the Arab states were intimidated into flight, or were expelled from their native countries, most of them reaching Israel.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The immediate reasons for this exodus were both the popular Arab hostility, including pogroms and anti-Jewish governmental measures, as well as the desire of many Jewish people to join the newly established State of Israel.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] In the three years following the war, about 700,000 Jews immigrated to Israel, where they were absorbed, fed and housed mainly along the borders and in former Palestinian lands.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Beginning in 1948, and continuing until 1972, an estimated 800,000 to 1,000,000 Jews migrated to Israel.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] From 1945 until the closure of 1952, more than 250,000 Jewish displaced persons lived in European refugee camps.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] About 136,000 of them immigrated to Israel.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] More than 270,000 Jews immigrated from Eastern Europe, mainly Romania and Poland (over 100,000 each).
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Overall 700,000 Jews settled in Israel, doubling its Jewish population.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Since the war, different historiographical traditions have interpreted the events of 1948 differently; in the words of the New Historian Avi Shlaim, "each side subscribes to a different version of events." In the Israeli narrative, the war is Israel's War of Independence.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] In the Palestinian narrative, the War of 1948 is inextricable from the Nakba, the Zionist movement is one of settler colonialism, and the Israelis are seen as conquerors and the Palestinians as victims.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The different narratives of 1948 reflect these different perceptions.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] An issue affecting the historiography of 1948 is access to sources and archives, which may have been destroyed, appropriated, censored, or otherwise made unavailable to some or all researchers.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Linguistic barriers represent another hurdle, as most research is published exclusively in the author's native language and is not translated.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The historiography of 1948 is tied to political legitimacy in the present and has implications for the Israeli–Palestinian conflict.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The narratives of 1948 have also had implications for Palestinian refugees.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Being the victors, the Israelis "were able to propagate more effectively than their opponents their version of this fateful war", in the words of Avi Shlaim.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Only in 1987 was that narrative effectively challenged outside the Arab world.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] It also portrays Israelis as morally superior, lacks political analysis, and gives undue weight to "the heroic feats of the Israeli fighters." This nationalist narrative was taught in Israeli schools and used for gaining legitimacy internationally.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] These writers came to be known as New Historians or "post-Zionists".
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Among their most vitriolic critics was Shabtai Teveth, biographer of David Ben-Gurion, who published "The New Historians", a series of four weekly full-page articles attacking the new historians, in Haaretz May 1989.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Teveth claimed that the new historiography was flawed in its practice and that it was politically motived, that it was pro-Palestinian and aimed to delegitimize the State of Israel.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Ilan Pappé identifies a turn in predominant Israeli narratives about 1948 in September 2000.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] In this period, the focus of Israeli historical writing on 1948 shifted largely from its human impact back to its military aspects.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Neo-Zionist writers were given selective access to top-secret material, to which writers critical of Zionism would not have been given access, and much of their work was published by the Israeli Ministry of Defense.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Among those Pappé associated with the neo-Zionist perspective were Benny Morris (who had become more outspokenly defensive of Zionism by this time), Daniel Gutwein, Mordechai Bar-On, Yoav Gelber, Tamir Goren, Arnon Golan, Alon Kadish, and Yoav Peleg, as well as the journal *Techelet*.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Yoav Gelber identifies Arif al-Arif's six volume *an-Nakba* written in Arabic in the 1950s as thorough and notable.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Palestinian narratives have focused on countering the dominant Zionist narrative; the preëminent Palestinian historian of 1948 Walid Khalidi has dedicated much of his career to disproving the official Israeli narrative that the 1948 Palestinian expulsion and flight was voluntary.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Without access to much in the way of archival materials, Palestinian historians have made use of oral history.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] In the narratives of the wider Arab-Muslim world, 1948 is seen as an "Arab debacle", representative of the region's social and political decline from its "glorious distant past".
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The American journalist Joan Peters' 1984 book *From Time Immemorial* had a massive impact on how 1948 was understood in popular and political narratives in the United States.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The 1948 Palestine war is also sometimes referred to as the 1948 Arab–Israeli war, the First Arab–Israeli war, or simply the 1948 war, although the term "Arab-Israeli war" often refers to the international phase of the war between Arab countries and Israel after May 15, 1948.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Palestinians and the Arab world often refer to the war as the Nakba ("the catastrophe"), while in Israel the conflict is known as the War of Independence (*Milhemet Ha'atzma'ut*).
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] A 1960 movie *Exodus* starring Paul Newman as Haganah rebel Ari Ben Canaan, a decorated former captain in the Jewish Brigade of the British Army in the Second World War, obtains a cargo ship.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] He smuggles 611 Jews out of a Cyprus camp run by the British and onto the ship for an illegal voyage to Mandatory Palestine.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] An American epic historical drama film about the founding of the State of Israel.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Produced and directed by Otto Preminger, the screenplay was adapted from the 1958 novel of the same name by Leon Uris.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] A 1966 movie *Cast a Giant Shadow* starring Kirk Douglas as US Colonel Mickey Marcus (1901–1948) who commanded units of the fledgling Israel Defense Forces during the 1948 Arab-Israeli War.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] One of the well known Israeli Machal soldiers, becoming Israel's first modern general (Hebrew: Aluf).
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Judith and colleagues are smuggled into Damascus, and after days of searching, they find Schiller.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] As they are about to capture him, Judith shoots and wounds him.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] Schiller is smuggled back to Palestine and interrogated.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] A 2015 PBS documentary, *A Wing and a Prayer*, depicts the Al Schwimmer-led airborne smuggling missions to arm Israel.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/1948-palestine-war] The 2021 historical drama film *Farha* tells the story of a Palestinian girl during the 1948 displacement of Palestinians from their homeland.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The **aftermath of World War II** saw the rise of two global superpowers, the United States and the Soviet Union.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Once allies during World War II, the United States and the Soviet Union became competitors on the world stage and engaged in the Cold War, so called because it never resulted in overt, declared total war between the two powers.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] It was instead characterized by espionage, political subversion, and proxy wars.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Western Europe was rebuilt through the American Marshall Plan, whereas Central and Eastern Europe fell under the Soviet sphere of influence and eventually behind an "Iron Curtain." Europe was divided into a U.S.-led Western Bloc and a Soviet-led Eastern Bloc.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Internationally, alliances with the two blocs gradually shifted, with some nations trying to stay out of the Cold War through the Non-Aligned Movement.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Cold War also saw a nuclear arms race between the two superpowers, and part of the reason that the Cold War never became a "hot" war was that the Soviet Union and the United States had nuclear deterrents against each other, leading to a mutually assured destruction standoff.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] As a consequence of the war, the Allies created the United Nations, an organization for international cooperation and diplomacy, similar to the League of Nations.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Members of the United Nations agreed to outlaw wars of aggression in an attempt to avoid a third world war.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The devastated great powers of Western Europe formed the European Coal and Steel Community, which later evolved into the European Economic Community and ultimately into the current European Union.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] This effort primarily began as an attempt to avoid another war between West Germany and France through economic cooperation and integration, and a common market for important natural resources.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The State of Israel was also established following the disestablishment of the British-ruled Mandatory Palestine and the 1948 Palestine War.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Nations in Sub-Saharan Africa achieved independence in the 1950s to 1970s.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The aftermath of World War II saw the rise of communist influence in East and Southeast Asia.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The People's Republic of China was founded after the Chinese Communist Party (CCP) emerged victorious from the Chinese Civil War in 1949, and the First Indochina War was fought between the Viet Minh government and France after the Japanese retreat.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Korean War led to the division of the Korean Peninsula between the communist North Korea and the Western-aligned South Korea.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] At the end of the war in Europe, tens of millions of people had been killed and even more were displaced, European economies had collapsed, and much of Europe's industrial infrastructure had been destroyed.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In response, in 1947 US Secretary of State George C.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Marshall devised the "European Recovery Program," which became known as the Marshall Plan.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Under the plan, from 1948 to 1952 the United States government allocated $13 billion (US$140 billion in 2024 dollars) for the reconstruction of affected countries in Western Europe.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] By the end of the war, the economy of the United Kingdom was one of severe privation, as a significant portion of its national wealth had been consumed by the war effort.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Until the introduction in 1941 of Lend-Lease aid from the United States, the UK had been spending its assets to purchase American equipment including aircraft and ships—over £437 million (equivalent to some £29 billion in 2024) on aircraft alone.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Lend-Lease came just before its reserves were exhausted.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Britain had placed 55% of its total labour force into war production.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In the spring of 1945, after the final defeat of Germany, the Labour Party withdrew from the wartime coalition government to oust Winston Churchill, forcing a general election.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Following a landslide victory, Labour held more than 60% of the seats in the House of Commons and formed a new government on 26 July 1945 under Clement Attlee, who had been Deputy Prime Minister in the coalition government.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Lend-Lease support to Britain on 2 September 1945 dealt a severe blow to the plans of the new government.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] It was only with the completion of the Anglo-American loan by the United States to Great Britain on 15 July 1946 that some measure of economic stability was restored.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] However, the loan was made primarily to support British overseas expenditure in the immediate post-war years and not to implement the Labour government's policies for domestic welfare reforms and the nationalisation of key industries.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Although the loan was agreed on reasonable terms, its conditions included what proved to be damaging fiscal conditions for sterling.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] From 1946 to 1948, the UK introduced bread rationing, which it had never done during the war.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviet Union suffered enormous losses in the war against Germany.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviet population decreased by about 27 million during the war; of these, 8.7 million were combatant deaths.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Soviet ex-POWs and civilians repatriated from abroad were suspected of having been Nazi collaborators, and 226,127 of them were sent to forced labour camps after scrutiny by Soviet intelligence, NKVD.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Many ex-POWs and young civilians were also conscripted to serve in the Red Army.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Others worked in labour battalions to rebuild infrastructure destroyed during the war.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Roughly a quarter of the Soviet Union's capital resources were destroyed, and industrial and agricultural output in 1945 fell far short of pre-war levels.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] To help rebuild the country, the Soviet government obtained limited credits from Britain and Sweden; it refused assistance offered by the United States under the Marshall Plan.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Instead, the Soviet Union coerced Soviet-occupied Central and Eastern Europe to supply machinery and raw materials.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Germany and former Nazi satellites made reparations to the Soviet Union.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The reconstruction programme emphasized heavy industry to the detriment of agriculture and consumer goods.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] By 1953, steel production was twice its 1940 level, but the production of many consumer goods and foodstuffs was lower than it had been in the late 1920s.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The immediate post-war period in Europe was dominated by the Soviet Union annexing, or converting into Soviet Socialist Republics, all the countries invaded and annexed by the Red Army driving the Germans out of central and eastern Europe.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] New satellite states were set up by the Soviets in Poland, Bulgaria, Hungary, Czechoslovakia, Romania, Albania, and East Germany; the last of these was created from the Soviet zone of occupation in Germany.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Yugoslavia emerged as an independent Communist state allied but not aligned with the Soviet Union, owing to the independent nature of the military victory of the Partisans of Josip Broz Tito during World War II in Yugoslavia.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Allies established the Far Eastern Commission and Allied Council for Japan to administer their occupation of that country while the establishment Allied Control Council, administered occupied Germany.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Following the Potsdam Conference agreements, the Soviet Union occupied and subsequently annexed the strategic island of Sakhalin.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In the east, the Sudetenland reverted to Czechoslovakia following the European Advisory Commission's decision to delimit German territory to be the territory it held on 31 December 1937.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Close to one-quarter of pre-war (1937) Nazi Germany was *de facto* annexed by the Allies; roughly 10 million Germans were either expelled from this territory or not permitted to return to it if they had fled during the war.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The remainder of Germany was partitioned into four zones of occupation, coordinated by the Allied Control Council.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Saar was detached and put into economic union with France in 1947.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In 1949, the Federal Republic of Germany was created out of the Western zones.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviet zone became the German Democratic Republic.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Germany paid reparations to the United Kingdom, France, and the Soviet Union, mainly in the form of dismantled factories, forced labour, and coal.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The German standard of living was to be reduced to its 1932 level.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Beginning immediately after the German surrender and continuing for the next two years, the U.S. and Britain pursued an "intellectual reparations" programme to harvest all technological and scientific know-how as well as all patents in Germany.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The value of these amounted to around $10 billion (US$120 billion in 2024 dollars).
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In accordance with the Paris Peace Treaties, 1947, reparations were also assessed from the countries of Italy, Romania, Hungary, Bulgaria, and Finland.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] US policy in post-war Germany from April 1945 until July 1947 had been that no help should be given to the Germans in rebuilding their nation, save for the minimum required to mitigate starvation.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Allies' immediate post-war "industrial disarmament" plan for Germany had been to destroy Germany's capability to wage war by complete or partial de-industrialization.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The first industrial plan for Germany signed in 1946, required the destruction of 1,500 manufacturing plants to lower German heavy industry output to roughly 50% of its 1938 level.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The dismantling of the West German industry ended in 1951.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] By 1950, equipment had been removed from 706 manufacturing plants, and steel production capacity had been reduced by 6.7 million tons.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Joint Chiefs of Staff and Generals Lucius D.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Marshall, the Truman administration accepted that economic recovery in Europe could not go forward without the reconstruction of the German industrial base on which it had previously been dependent.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] From 1948 onward West Germany also became a minor beneficiary of the Marshall Plan.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Volunteer organizations had initially been forbidden to send food, but in early 1946 the Council of Relief Agencies Licensed to Operate in Germany was founded.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The prohibition against sending CARE Packages to individuals in Germany was rescinded on 5 June 1946.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Following the German surrender, the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) was prohibited from providing aid such as food or visiting POW camps for Germans inside Germany.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] However, after making approaches to the Allies in the autumn of 1945 it was allowed to investigate the camps in the United Kingdom and French occupation zones of Germany, as well as to provide relief to the prisoners held there.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] On 4 February 1946, the ICRC was also permitted to visit and assist prisoners in the U.S. occupation zone of Germany, although only with very small quantities of food.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The ICRC petitioned successfully for improvements to be made in the living conditions of German POWs.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The German people as a whole, especially its youth, were traumatized psychologically by the previous decade of Nazi rule, with major cities and infrastructure destroyed by Allied bombardments.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] At the end of the war, major cities were devastated, food shortages ensued, and a wave of denazification occurred throughout occupied Germany.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] As France was liberated from German occupation, an *épuration* (purge) of real and suspected Nazi collaborators began.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] At first, this was undertaken in an extralegal manner by the French Resistance (called the *épuration sauvage*, "wild purge").
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] French women who had had romantic liaisons with German soldiers were publicly humiliated and had their heads shaved.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] There was also a wave of summary executions estimated to have killed about 10,000 people.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] When the Provisional Government of the French Republic established control, the *Épuration légale* ("legal purge") began.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] There were no international war crimes trials for French collaborators, who were tried in the domestic courts.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Approximately 300,000 cases were investigated; 120,000 people were given various sentences including 6,763 death sentences (of which only 791 were carried out).
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Most convicts were given amnesty a few years later.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The aftermath of World War II left Italy with an anger against the monarchy for its endorsement of the Fascist regime for the previous twenty years.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] These frustrations contributed to a revival of the Italian republican movement.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In the 1946 Italian constitutional referendum, held on 2 June, a day celebrated since as *Festa della Repubblica*, the Italian monarchy was abolished, having been associated with the deprivations of the war and the Fascist rule, especially in the North, and Italy became a republic.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] This was the first time that Italian women voted at the national level, and the second time overall considering the local elections that were held a few months earlier in some cities.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] King Victor Emmanuel III's son, King Umberto II, was forced to abdicate and exiled.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Republican Constitution was approved on 1 January 1948, resulting from the work of a Constituent Assembly formed by the representatives of all the anti-fascist forces that contributed to the defeat of Nazi and Fascist forces during the liberation of Italy.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The 1947 Treaty of Peace compelled Italy to pay $360 million (US dollars at 1938 prices) in war reparations: $125 million to Yugoslavia, $105 million to Greece, $100 million to the Soviet Union, $25 million to Ethiopia, and $5 million to Albania.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In 1954 the Free Territory of Trieste, an independent territory between northern Italy and Yugoslavia under direct responsibility of the UN Security Council, was divided between the two states, Italy and Yugoslavia.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Italian border that applies today has existed since 1975, when Trieste was formally re-annexed to Italy after the Treaty of Osimo.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In 1950 Italian Somaliland was made a United Nations Trust Territory under Italian administration until 1 July 1960.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Federal State of Austria had been annexed by Germany in 1938 (Anschluss, this union was banned by the Treaty of Versailles).
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Austria (called Ostmark by the Germans) was separated from Germany and divided into four zones of occupation.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] With the Austrian State Treaty, these zones reunited in 1955 to become the Republic of Austria.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Following the war, the Allies rescinded the Empire of Japan's pre-war annexations such as Manchuria, and Korea became militarily occupied by the United States in the south and by the Soviet Union in the north.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Philippines and Guam were returned to the United States.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Burma, Malaya, and Singapore were returned to Britain and Indochina back to France.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Dutch East Indies was to be handed back to the Dutch but was resisted leading to the Indonesian war for independence.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Roosevelt had secretly traded the Japanese Kurils and south Sakhalin to the Soviet Union in return for Soviet entry into the war with Japan.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviet Union annexed the Kuril Islands, provoking the Kuril Islands dispute, which is ongoing, as Russia continues to occupy the islands.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Hundreds of thousands of Japanese were forced to relocate to the Japanese main islands.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Okinawa became a main U.S. staging point.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The U.S. covered large areas of it with military bases and continued to occupy it until 1972, years after the end of the occupation of the main islands.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] To skirt the Geneva Convention, the Allies classified many Japanese soldiers as Japanese Surrendered Personnel (JSP) instead of POWs and used them as forced labour until 1947.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The United Kingdom, France, and the Netherlands used JSP to support their military operations in the region after World War II.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] General Douglas MacArthur established the International Military Tribunal for the Far East.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Allies collected reparations from Japan.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] To further remove Japan as a potential future military threat, the Far Eastern Commission decided to de-industrialize Japan, to reduce the Japanese standard of living to what prevailed between 1930 and 1934.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In the end, the de-industrialisation programme in Japan was implemented to a lesser degree than the one in Germany.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Japan received emergency aid from GARIOA, as did Germany.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In early 1946, the Licensed Agencies for Relief in Asia were formed and permitted to supply Japanese with food and clothes.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In April 1948 the Johnston Committee Report recommended that the economy of Japan should be reconstructed due to the high cost to US taxpayers of continuous emergency aid.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Survivors of the atomic bombings of Hiroshima and Nagasaki, known as *hibakusha* (被爆者), were ostracized by Japanese society.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Japan provided no special assistance to these people until 1952.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] By the 65th anniversary of the bombings, total casualties from the initial attack and later deaths reached about 270,000 in Hiroshima and 150,000 in Nagasaki.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] About 230,000 hibakusha were still alive as of 2010, and about 2,200 were suffering from radiation-caused illnesses as of 2007.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In the Winter War of 1939–1940, the Soviet Union invaded neutral Finland and annexed some of its territory.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] From 1941 until 1944, Finland aligned itself with Nazi Germany in a failed effort to regain lost territories from the Soviets.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Finland retained its independence following the war but remained subject to Soviet-imposed constraints in its domestic affairs.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In 1940 the Soviet Union invaded and annexed the neutral Baltic states, Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In June 1941, the Soviet governments of the Baltic states carried out mass deportations of "enemies of the people"; as a result, many treated the invading Nazis as liberators when they invaded only a week later.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Atlantic Charter promised self-determination to people deprived of it during the war.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The British Prime Minister, Winston Churchill, argued for a weaker interpretation of the Charter to permit the Soviet Union to continue to control the Baltic states.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In March 1944 the US accepted Churchill's view that the Atlantic Charter did not apply to the Baltic states.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] With the return of Soviet troops at the end of the war, the Forest Brothers mounted a guerrilla war.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] An estimated 1 million military and civilian Filipinos were killed from all causes; of these 131,028 were listed as killed in 72 war crime events.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] According to a United States analysis released years after the war, U.S. casualties were 10,380 dead and 36,550 wounded; Japanese dead were 255,795.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] As a result of the new borders drawn by the victorious nations, large populations suddenly found themselves in hostile territory.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviet Union took over areas formerly controlled by Germany, Finland, Poland and Japan.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Poland lost the Kresy region (about half of its pre-war territory) and received most of Germany east of the Oder–Neisse line, including the industrial regions of Silesia.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The German state of the Saar was temporarily a protectorate of France but later returned to German administration.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] As set forth at Potsdam, approximately 12 million people were expelled from Germany, including 7 million from Germany proper, and three million from the Sudetenland.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] During the war, the United States government interned approximately 110,000 Japanese Americans and Japanese who lived along the Pacific coast of the United States in the wake of Imperial Japan's attack on Pearl Harbor.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Canada interned approximately 22,000 Japanese Canadians, 14,000 of whom were born in Canada.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] After the war, some internees chose to return to Japan, while most remained in North America.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviet Union expelled at least 2 million Poles from the east of the new border approximating the Curzon Line.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] This estimate is uncertain as neither the Polish Communist government nor the Soviet government kept track of the number of expelled people.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The number of Polish citizens inhabiting Polish borderlands (Kresy region) was about 13 million before World War II broke out according to official Polish statistics.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Polish citizens killed in the war that originated from the Polish borderlands territory (killed by either the German Nazi regime or the Soviet regime, or expelled to distant parts of Siberia) were accounted as Russian, Ukrainian, or Belarusian casualties of war in official Soviet historiography.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] This fact imposes additional difficulties in making the correct estimation of the number of Polish citizens forcibly transferred after the war.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The border change also reversed the results of the 1919–1920 Polish–Soviet War.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Former Polish cities such as Lwów came under the control of the Ukrainian Soviet Socialist Republic.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Additionally, the Soviet Union transferred more than two million people within their borders; these included Germans, Finns, Crimean Tatars and Chechens.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] As Soviet troops marched across the Balkans, they committed rapes and robberies in Romania, Hungary, Czechoslovakia, and Yugoslavia.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The population of Bulgaria was largely spared of this treatment, possibly due to a sense of ethnic kinship or to the leadership of Marshal Fyodor Tolbukhin.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The population of Germany was treated significantly worse.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Rape and murder of German civilians was as bad as, and sometimes worse than, Nazi propaganda had anticipated.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Political officers encouraged Soviet troops to seek revenge and terrorise the German population.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] On "the basis of *Hochrechnungen* (projections or estimations), [...] 1.9 million German women altogether were raped at the end of the war by Red Army soldiers." About one-third of all German women in Berlin were raped by Soviet forces, and a substantial minority were raped multiple times.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In Berlin, contemporary hospital records indicate between 95,000 and 130,000 women were raped by Soviet troops.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] About 10,000 of these women died, mostly by suicide.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Over 4.5 million Germans fled towards the West.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviets initially had no rules against their troops "fraternising" with German women, but by 1947 they started to isolate their troops from the German population in an attempt to stop rape and robbery by the troops.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Not all Soviet soldiers participated in these activities.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Foreign reports of Soviet brutality were denounced as false.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Rape, robbery, and murder were blamed on German bandits impersonating Soviet soldiers.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Some justified Soviet brutality towards German civilians based on previous brutality of German troops toward Russian civilians.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Until the reunification of Germany, East German histories virtually ignored the actions of Soviet troops, and Russian histories still tend to do so.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Reports of mass rapes by Soviet troops were often dismissed as anti-Communist propaganda or the normal byproduct of war.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Rapes also occurred under other Allied forces in Europe, though the majority were committed by Soviet troops.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In a letter to the editor of *Time* published in September 1945, a U.S.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Lilly assumed that only 5% of rapes by American soldiers were reported, making 17,000 GI rapes a possibility, while analysts estimate that 50% of (ordinary peacetime) rapes are reported.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Supporting Lilly's lower figure is the "crucial difference" that for World War II military rapes "it was the commanding officer, not the victim, who brought charges." According to German historian Miriam Gebhardt, as many as 190,000 women were raped by U.S. soldiers in Germany.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] German soldiers left many war children behind in nations such as France and Denmark, which were occupied for an extended period.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] After the war, the children and their mothers often suffered recriminations.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In Norway, the "Tyskerunger" (German-kids) suffered greatly.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] During the Italian campaign, the Goumiers, French Moroccan colonial troops attached to the French Expeditionary Forces, have been accused of committing rape and murder against the Italian peasant communities, mostly targeting civilian women and girls, as well as a few men and boys.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In Italy the victims of these acts were described as *Marocchinate* meaning literally "Moroccaned" (or people who have been subjected to acts committed by Moroccans).
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] According to Italian victims associations, a total of more than 7,000 civilians, including children, were raped by Goumiers.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In the first few weeks of the American military occupation of Japan, rape and other violent crime was widespread in naval ports like Yokohama and Yokosuka but declined shortly afterward.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] There were 1,336 reported rapes during the first 10 days of the occupation of Kanagawa prefecture.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Historian Toshiyuki Tanaka relates that in Yokohama, the capital of the prefecture, there were 119 known rapes in September 1945.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Historians Eiji Takemae and Robert Ricketts state that, "When U.S. paratroopers landed in Sapporo, an orgy of looting, sexual violence, and drunken brawling ensued.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Gang rapes and other sex atrocities were not infrequent" and some of the rape victims committed suicide.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Eighth Army, recorded that in the one instance when the Japanese formed a self-help vigilante guard to protect women from off-duty GIs, the Eighth Army ordered armored vehicles in the battle array into the streets and arrested the leaders, and the leaders received long prison terms.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Rape committed by U.S. soldiers occupying Okinawa was also a notable phenomenon.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] According to Toshiyuki Tanaka, 76 cases of rape or rape-murder were reported during the first five years of the American occupation of Okinawa.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] However, he claims this is probably not the true figure, as most cases were unreported.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] During World War II, the Japanese military established brothels filled with "comfort women," a euphemism for the 200,000 girls and women who were forced into sexual slavery for Japanese soldiers.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In Confucian nations like Korea and China, where premarital sex is considered shameful, the subject of the "comfort women" was ignored for decades after 1945 as the victims were considered pariahs.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Dutch comfort women brought a successful case before the Batavia Military Tribunal in 1948.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Many allied leaders felt that war between the United States and the Soviet Union was likely.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] On 19 May 1945, the United States Under-Secretary of State Joseph Grew went so far as to say that it was inevitable.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] On 5 March 1946, in his "Sinews of Peace" (Iron Curtain) speech at Westminster College in Fulton, Missouri, Winston Churchill said "a shadow" had fallen over Europe.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] He described Stalin as having dropped an "Iron Curtain" between East and West.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Stalin responded by charging that co-existence between communist countries and the West was impossible.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In mid-1948 the Soviet Union imposed a blockade on the Western zone of occupation in Berlin.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Due to the rising tension in Europe and concerns over further Soviet expansion, American planners came up with a contingency plan code-named *Operation Dropshot* in 1949.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] It considered possible nuclear and conventional war with the Soviet Union and its allies to counter a Soviet takeover of Western Europe, the Near East, and parts of Eastern Asia that they anticipated would begin around 1957.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In response, the United States. would saturate the Soviet Union with atomic and high-explosive bombs, and then invade and occupy the country.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The approach entailed a major buildup of U.S. nuclear forces and a corresponding reduction in America's non-nuclear ground and naval strength.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In Greece, civil war broke out in 1946 between Anglo-American-supported royalist forces and communist-led forces, with the royalist forces emerging as the victors.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The U.S. launched a massive programme of military and economic aid to Greece and to neighbouring Turkey, arising from a fear that the Soviet Union stood on the verge of breaking through the NATO defence line to the oil-rich Middle East.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] On 12 March 1947, to gain Congressional support for the aid, President Truman described the aid as promoting democracy in defence of the "Free World," a principle that became known as the Truman Doctrine.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The United States sought to promote an economically strong and politically united Western Europe to counter the threat posed by the Soviet Union.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] This was done openly using tools such as the European Recovery Program, which encouraged European economic integration.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The International Authority for the Ruhr, designed to keep German industry down and controlled, evolved into the European Coal and Steel Community (ECOSOC), a founding pillar of the European Union.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The United States also worked covertly to promote European integration, for example using the American Committee on United Europe to funnel funds to European federalist movements.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] To ensure that Western Europe could withstand the Soviet military threat, the Western European Union was founded in 1948 and NATO in 1949.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The first NATO Secretary General, Lord Ismay, famously stated the organisation's goal was, "to keep the Russians out, the Americans in, and the Germans down." However without the manpower and industrial output of West Germany, no conventional defence of Western Europe had any hope of succeeding.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] To remedy this, in 1950 the United States sought to promote the European Defence Community, which would have included a rearmed West Germany.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The attempt was dashed when the French Parliament rejected it.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] On 9 May 1955, West Germany was instead admitted to NATO; the immediate result was the creation of the Warsaw Pact five days later.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In Asia, the surrender of Japanese forces was complicated by the split between East and West as well as by the movement toward national self-determination in European colonial territories.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Decisions to decolonize British India led to an agreement to partition the country along religious lines into two independent dominions: India and Pakistan.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The partition resulted in communal violence and massive displacements of the population.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] It is often described as the largest mass human migration and one of the largest refugee crises in history.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] As agreed to at the Yalta Conference, the Soviet Union declared war on Japan.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Soviet forces invaded Manchuria which led to the collapse of the Manchukuo and expulsion of all Japanese settlers from the puppet state.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Soviet Union dismantled the industrial base in Manchuria that the Japanese had built up and it subsequently became a base for the Communist Chinese forces due to the area being under Soviet occupation.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Following the end of the war, the Kuomintang (KMT) party (led by generalissimo Chiang Kai-shek) and the Communist Chinese forces resumed fighting each other, which they had temporarily suspended in order to fight Japan.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The fight against the Japanese occupiers had strengthened popular support among the Chinese people for the Communist forces while it weakened the KMT, which depleted its strength fighting them.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Full-scale war between the KMT and CCF broke out in June 1946.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Despite United States' support for the Kuomintang, Communist forces ultimately prevailed and they established the People's Republic of China (PRC) on the mainland.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The KMT forces retreated to the island of Taiwan in 1949 where they established the Republic of China (ROC).
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] With the Communist victory in the civil war, the Soviet Union gave up its claim to military bases in China that were given to it by its Western Allies at the end of World War II.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] While large scale hostilities largely ceased by 1950, intermittent clashes occurred between the two from 1950 to 1979.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Taiwan unilaterally declared the civil war over in 1991, but no formal peace treaty or truce has been signed and the PRC continues to officially see Taiwan as a breakaway province that rightfully belongs to it.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The outbreak of the Korean War a few months after the conclusion of the Chinese Civil War and continued U.S. support for the KMT were the main reasons that prevented the PRC from invading Taiwan.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] At the Yalta Conference, the Allies agreed that an undivided post-war Korea would be placed under 4-power multinational trusteeship.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] After Japan's surrender, this agreement was modified to a joint Soviet-American occupation of Korea.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The agreement was that Korea would be divided and occupied by the Soviets from the north and the Americans from the south.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Korea, formerly under Japanese rule, and which had been partially occupied by the Red Army following the Soviet Union's entry into the war against Japan, was divided at the 38th parallel on the orders of the U.S.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] A United States military government in southern Korea was established in the capital city of Seoul.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The US military commander, Lieutenant General John R.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Hodge, enlisted many former Japanese administrative officials to serve in this government.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] North of the military line, the Soviets administered the disarming and demobilisation of repatriated Korean nationalist guerrillas who had fought on the side of Chinese nationalists against the Japanese in Manchuria during World War II.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Simultaneously, the Soviets enabled a build-up of heavy armaments to pro-communist forces in the north.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The military line became a political line in 1948, when separate republics emerged on both sides of the 38th parallel, each republic claiming to be the legitimate government of Korea.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] It culminated in the north invading the south, start of the Korean War two years later.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Labour and civil unrest broke out in the British colony of Malaya in 1946.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] A state of emergency was declared by the colonial authorities in 1948 with the outbreak of acts of terrorism.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The situation deteriorated into a full-scale anti-colonial insurgency, or Anti-British National Liberation War as the insurgents referred to it, led by the Malayan National Liberation Army (MNLA), the military wing of the Malayan Communist Party.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Malayan Emergency would endure for the next twelve years, ending in 1960.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In 1967, communist leader Chin Peng reopened hostilities, culminating in a second emergency that lasted until 1989.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Events after World War II in French Indochina, which consisted of the territories of modern-day Vietnam, Laos and Cambodia, set the stage for Indochina wars.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] By 1941 during World War II, Japan gained full military access across Indochina and established a fragile dual colonial rule that maintained French administration while facilitating Japanese preparations for Southeast Asian operations.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The communist-controlled Viet Minh Front was formed in 1941 to fight against both Japanese and French forces.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Because the French colonial authorities began holding secret talks with Free France, the Japanese carried out a coup d’état on 9 March 1945.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] When Japan surrendered in August, this created a power vacuum, and the Viet Minh seized power during the August Revolution, declaring the independence of the Democratic Republic of Vietnam.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] However, the Allies (including the Soviet Union) all agreed that the area belonged to the French.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] From 1945 onward, the Vietnamese were locked in civil conflicts over the destiny of their post-colonial state after the ousting of the French and the surrender of Japan.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Meanwhile, Nationalist Chinese forces moved in from the north and British from the south (as the French were unable to do so immediately themselves) and then handed power to the French, a process completed by March 1946.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Attempts to integrate the Democratic Republic of Vietnam with French rule failed and the Viet Minh launched their rebellion against the French rule starting the First Indochina War that same year (the Viet Minh organized common fronts to fight the French in Laos and Cambodia).
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The war ended in 1954 with the French withdrawal and the partition of Vietnam, which was intended to be temporary until elections could be held.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Democratic Republic of Vietnam controlled the North, while the State of Vietnam held the South.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Ngo Dinh Diem, backed by the United States in his refusal to hold elections, which he claimed would be unfair due to communist rigging, established the Republic of Vietnam.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Communist insurgents in the South formed the NLF under the direct guidance of North Vietnam to fight against the South Vietnamese government, a conflict that ultimately ended with North Vietnam conquering the South in April 1975.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Japan invaded and occupied the Dutch East Indies during the war and replaced the colonial government with a new administration.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Although the top positions were held by Japanese officers, the internment of all Dutch citizens meant that Indonesians filled many leadership and administrative positions.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Following the Japanese surrender in August 1945, Indonesian nationalist leaders such as Sukarno and Mohammad Hatta declared Indonesia as independent.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] A four-and-a-half-year struggle followed as the Dutch tried to re-establish their rule in colony, using a significant portion of their Marshall Plan aid to this end.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The Dutch were aided by British forces for the first phase of the conflict until the United Kingdom withdrew.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] The British also initially used 35,000 Japanese Surrendered Personnel to support their military operations in Indonesia.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] Although Dutch forces re-occupied most of Indonesia, an Indonesian guerrilla campaign supported by the majority of Indonesians ensured, and ultimately international opinion favoured independence.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p01] In December 1949, the Netherlands formally recognised Indonesian sovereignty.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] British covert operations in the Baltic States, which began in 1944 against the Nazis, escalated following the war.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] In Operation Jungle, the Secret Intelligence Service (known as MI6) recruited and trained Estonians, Latvians, and Lithuanians for the clandestine work in the Baltic states between 1948 and 1955.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Leaders of the operation included Alfons Rebane, Stasys Žymantas, and Rūdolfs Silarājs.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The agents were transported under the cover of the "British Baltic Fishery Protection Service." They launched from British-occupied Germany, using a converted World War II E-boat captained and crewed by former members of the wartime German navy.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] British intelligence also trained and infiltrated anti-communist agents into Soviet Union from across the Finnish border, with orders to assassinate Soviet officials.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] In the end, counter-intelligence supplied to the KGB by Kim Philby allowed the KGB to penetrate and ultimately gain control of MI6's entire intelligence network in the Baltic states.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Vietnam and the Middle East would later damage the reputation gained by the U.S. during its successes in Europe.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The KGB believed that the Third World rather than Europe was the arena in which it could win the Cold War.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Moscow would in later years fuel an arms buildup in Africa.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] In later years, African countries used as proxies in the Cold War would often become "failed states" of their own.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] When the divisions of postwar Europe began to emerge, the war crimes programmes and denazification policies of Britain and the United States were relaxed in favour of recruiting German scientists, especially nuclear and long-range rocket scientists.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Many of these, prior to their capture, had worked on developing the German V-2 long-range rocket at the Baltic coast German Army Research Center Peenemünde.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] In Operation Paperclip, beginning in 1945, the United States imported 1,600 German scientists and technicians as part of the intellectual reparations owed to the US and the UK, including about $10 billion (US$165 billion in 2025 dollars) in patents and industrial processes.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The wartime activities of some Operation Paperclip scientists would later be investigated.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Arthur Rudolph left the United States in 1984 in order to not be prosecuted.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Similarly, Georg Rickhey, who came to the United States under Operation Paperclip in 1946, was returned to Germany to stand trial at the Mittelbau-Dora war crimes trial in 1947.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Following his acquittal, he returned to the United States in 1948 and eventually became a U.S. citizen.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Soviets began Operation Osoaviakhim in 1946.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] NKVD and Soviet army units effectively deported thousands of military-related technical specialists from the Soviet occupation zone of post-war Germany to the Soviet Union.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Soviets used 92 trains to transport the specialists and their families, an estimated 10,000 to 15,000 people.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Much related equipment was also moved, the aim being to virtually transplant research and production centres, such as the relocated V-2 rocket centre at Mittelwerk Nordhausen, from Germany to the Soviet Union.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Among the people moved were Helmut Gröttrup and about two hundred scientists and technicians from Mittelwerk.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Personnel were also taken from AEG, BMW's Stassfurt jet propulsion group, IG Farben's Leuna chemical works, Junkers, Schott AG, Siebel, Telefunken, and Carl Zeiss AG.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The operation was commanded by NKVD deputy Colonel General Serov, outside the control of the local Soviet Military Administration.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The major reason for the operation was the Soviet fear of being condemned for noncompliance with Allied Control Council agreements on the liquidation of German military installations.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Some Western observers thought Operation Osoaviakhim was a retaliation for the failure of the Socialist Unity Party in elections, though Osoaviakhim was clearly planned before that.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] As a general consequence of the war and in an effort to maintain international peace, the Allies formed the United Nations, which officially came into existence on 24 October 1945.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The United Nations replaced the defunct League of Nations as an intergovernmental organization.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The League was formally dissolved on 20 April 1946, but had in practice ceased to function in 1939, being unable to stop the outbreak of World War II.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The UN inherited some of the bodies of the League, such as the International Labour Organization.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] League of Nations mandate, mostly territories that had changed hands in World War I, became United Nations trust territories.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] South West Africa, an exception, was still governed under terms of the original mandate.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] As the successor body to the League, the United Nations still assumed a supervisory role over the territory.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Free City of Danzig, a semi-autonomous city-state that was partly overseen by the League, became part of Poland.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The United Nations adopted the Universal Declaration of Human Rights in 1948, "as a common standard of achievement for all peoples and all nations." The Soviet Union abstained from voting on adoption of the declaration.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The U.S. did not ratify the social and economic rights sections.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The five major Allied powers were given permanent membership in the UN Security Council.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The permanent members can veto any Security Council resolution, the only UN decisions that are binding according to international law.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The five powers at the time of founding were: the United States, United Kingdom, France, Soviet Union, and Republic of China.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Republic of China lost the Chinese Civil War and retreated to the island of Taiwan by 1950 but continued to be a permanent member of the Council even though the *de facto* state in control of mainland China was the People's Republic of China (PRC).
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] This was changed in 1971 when the PRC was given the permanent membership previously held by the Republic of China.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Russia inherited the permanent membership of the Soviet Union in 1991 after the dissolution of that state.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Japanese holdouts persisted on various islands in the Pacific Theatre until at least 1974.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Although all hostilities are now resolved, a peace treaty has never been signed between Japan and Russia due to the Kuril Islands dispute.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] By the end of the war, the European economy had collapsed with some 70% of its industrial infrastructure destroyed.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The property damage in the Soviet Union consisted of complete or partial destruction of 1,710 cities and towns, 70,000 villages/hamlets, and 31,850 industrial establishments.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The strength of the economic recovery following the war varied throughout the world, though in general, it was quite robust, particularly in the United States.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] In Europe, West Germany, after having continued to decline economically during the first years of the Allied occupation, later experienced a remarkable recovery, and had by the end of the 1950s doubled production from its pre-war levels.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Italy came out of the war in poor economic condition, but by the 1950s, the Italian economy was marked by stability and high growth.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] France rebounded quickly and enjoyed rapid economic growth and modernisation under the Monnet Plan.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The United Kingdom, by contrast, was in a state of economic ruin after the war and continued to experience relative economic decline for decades to follow.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The Soviet Union also experienced a rapid increase in production in the immediate post-war era.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Japan experienced rapid economic growth, becoming one of the most powerful economies in the world by the 1980s.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] China, following the conclusion of its civil war, was essentially bankrupt.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] By 1953, economic restoration seemed fairly successful as production had resumed pre-war levels.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Although China's growth rate mostly persisted, it was severely disrupted by the economic experiments of the Great Leap Forward, due to the resulting famine that caused the deaths of 15 to 55 million people.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] At the end of the war, the United States produced roughly half of the world's industrial output.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The United States, of course, had been spared industrial and civilian devastation.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Further, much of its pre-war industry had been converted to wartime usage.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] As a result, with its industrial and civilian base in much better shape than most of the world, the United States embarked on an economic expansion unseen in human history.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] U.S. gross domestic product increased from $228 billion in 1945 to just under $1.7 trillion in 1975.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] In 1951 several laws were passed, ending the denazification.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] As a result, many people with a former Nazi past ended up again in the political apparatus of West Germany.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] West German President Walter Scheel and Chancellor Kurt Georg Kiesinger were both former members of the Nazi Party.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] In 1957, 77% of the West German Ministry of Justice's senior officials were former Nazi Party members.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Konrad Adenauer's State Secretary Hans Globke had played a major role in drafting antisemitic Nuremberg Race Laws in Nazi Germany.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The historical consensus is that West Germany's efforts at denazification proved wanting.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] In 2019, the then Germany’s President Frank-Walter Steinmeier has apologized, in Wieluń in Poland, on behalf of Germany, for the “German tyranny” in World War II over Poland.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Unexploded ordnance continues to pose a danger in the present day.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] In 2017, 50 thousand people were evacuated from Hanover so World War II era bombs could be defused.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] As of 2023, it is still thought that thousands of unexploded bombs remain from World War II.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] When World War II ended, scientists did not have procedures for safe disposal of chemical arsenals.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] At the direction of the UK, US and Russia, chemical weapons were loaded onto ships by the metric ton and dumped into the sea.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] The exact locations of the dumping are not known due to poor record keeping, but it is estimated that 1 million metric tons of chemical weapons remain on the ocean floor where they are rusting and pose the risk of leaks.
[src:aftermath-of-world-war-ii/aftermath-of-world-war-ii-p02] Sulfur mustard exposure has been reported in some parts of coastal Italy and sulfur mustard bombs have been found as far as Delaware, likely brought in with the shellfish cargo.
